gn=\"left\" | {{flagicon|Federal District (Brazil)}} [[Federal District (Brazil)|Federal District]]\n| 56,6%\n| 25,8%\n| 3,5%\n| 0,2%\n| 3,7%\n| 9,2%\n| 1,0%\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|Esp\u00edrito Santo}} [[Esp\u00edrito Santo]]\n| 52,2%\n| 33,1%\n| 1%\n| 0,2%\n| 2%\n| 10,4%\n| 1,1%\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|Acre}} [[Acre]]\n| 51,9%\n| 32,7%\n| 0,6%\n| 0,0%\n| 2,9%\n| 11,8%\n| 0,1%\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|Roraima}} [[Roraima]]\n| 47,9%\n| 30,3%\n| 0,9%\n| 0,1%\n| 6,6%\n| 13%\n| 1,2%\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|Rond\u00f4nia}} [[Rond\u00f4nia]]\n| 47,6%\n| 33,8%\n| 0,6%\n| 0,0%\n| 3,7%\n| 13,3%\n| 1,0%\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|Rio de Janeiro}} [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|Rio de Janeiro]]\n| 45,8%\n| 29,4%\n| 4,0%\n| 0,9%\n| 4,3%\n| 14,6%\n| 1,0%\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Demographics of Brazil]]\n* [[Roman Catholicism in Brazil]]\n* [[Protestantism in Brazil]]\n* [[Islam in Brazil]]\n* [[History of the Jews in Brazil|Judaism in Brazil]]\n* [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in Brazil]]\n* [[Hinduism in Brazil]]\n* [[Religion in Latin America]]\n\n== Pie Chart notes ==\n{{notelist|group=pie}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Brazil topics}}\n{{South America topic|Religion in}}\n\n[[Category:Religion in Brazil| ]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religion_in_Brazil"}
{"title_page": "The Cranberries", "text_new": "{{About|the rock band|the plant species|Cranberry|other uses|Cranberry (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Irish rock band}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = The Cranberries\n| image = The Cranberries en Barcelona 8.jpg\n| alt = Noel Hogan holding a guitar and Dolores O'Riordan singing into a microphone\n| caption = The Cranberries, guitarist [[Noel Hogan]] and lead singer [[Dolores O'Riordan]] in [[Barcelona]], 2010\n| alias = The Cranberry Saw Us<br/>(1989\u20131990)\n| landscape = yes\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Limerick]], Ireland\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Irish folk]]}}\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[post-punk]]\n}}\n| years_active = {{flatlist|\n* 1989\u20132003\n* 2009\u20132019<ref name=\"officialcharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-cranberries-open-up-about-the-last-days-of-singer-dolores-o-riordan-she-was-on-a-roll__24108/|title=\"She was on a roll\": The Cranberries open up about the last days of singer Dolores O'Riordan|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Xeric\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Downtown Records|Downtown]]\n* [[Cooking Vinyl]]\n* [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[D.A.R.K.|Jetlag]]\n| website = {{URL|cranberries.com}}\n| past_members = \n* Mike Hogan\n* [[Noel Hogan]]\n* Fergal Lawler\n* Niall Quinn\n* [[Dolores O'Riordan]]<!-- Please do not add the notice about her death, as it doesn't belong in the infobox. -->\n}}\n'''The Cranberries''' were an Irish [[Rock music|rock]] band<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/best-cranberries-songs-20-essential-tracks/|title=Limerick alt.rock icons The Cranberries |website=udiscovermusic.com|date=9 October 2019|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> formed in [[Limerick]], Ireland in 1989 by lead singer Niall Quinn, guitarist [[Noel Hogan]], bassist Mike Hogan, and drummer Fergal Lawler. Quinn was replaced as lead singer by [[Dolores O'Riordan]] in 1990.<ref name=\"NYT Hauser\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/15/obituaries/dolores-oriordan-dead.html|title=Celtic-influenced vocals\u2014tuneful, punk-derived, guitar-driven songs|website=New York Times.|date=15 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Ow5Gp|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The band officially classify themselves as an [[alternative rock]] group,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1978669/the-10-best-cranberries-songs/franchises/list/|title=The Cranberries were one of the alt-rock era\u2019s biggest successes.|website=www.stereogum.com|date=16 January 2018 |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/67251/The-Cranberries-No-Need-to-Argue/|title=The Cranberries, a quartet out of Dublin with a rich, clean and mature alternative rock sound.|website=www.sputnikmusic.com|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> but incorporate aspects of [[indie pop]], [[post-punk]], [[folk rock]] and [[pop rock]] into their sound.<ref name=\"UL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ul.ie/ceremonies/cranberries|title='Indie' guitar sound and distinctive Celtic-tinged lilting vocal style.|website=www.ul.ie/ceremonies|date=18 January 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/sJ3Vd|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.post-punk.com/dolores-oriordan-cranberries-passed-away/|title=post-punk.com The Cranberries' lead singer Dolores O'Riordan has died.|website=www.post-punk.com|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/the-cranberries-a-sweet-and-lingering-fruit-of-the-90s-11209817|title=Ireland's biggest export since U2 started off with songs of innocence and became worthy successors of the post-punk movement.|website=news.sky.com/|date=6 September 2018|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@nilegirl/what-the-cranberries-taught-me-about-music-activism-and-love-songs-364bd0e8122|title=The indie-pop/pop-rock/Irish folk group that dominated the earlier part of the nineties.|website=medium.com|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Hauser\"/>\n\nThe Cranberries rose to international fame in the 1990s with their debut album ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'', which became a commercial success, and achieved five top 20 albums on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart : ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'', ''[[No Need to Argue]]'', ''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'', ''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]'' and ''[[Stars: The Best of 1992-2002]]''<ref name=\"US\">{{cite web\n |url=https://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/searchResult.jsp?configType=BBCOM_SIMPLEDEFAULT&pubList=Billboard&an=bbcom&action=Submit&kw=&exposeNavigation=true&keyword=The+Cranberries&submit.x=27&submit.y=14&submit=Submit&searchType=ARTICLE_SEARCH \n |title=American Chart \n |website=Billboard.com \n |accessdate=24 June 2008 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080801201840/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/searchResult.jsp?configType=BBCOM_SIMPLEDEFAULT&pubList=Billboard&an=bbcom&action=Submit&kw=&exposeNavigation=true&keyword=The%2BCranberries&submit.x=27&submit.y=14&submit=Submit&searchType=ARTICLE_SEARCH \n |archivedate=1 August 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> as well as having eight top 20 singles on the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart : \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\", \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\", \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\", \"[[Ode to My Family]]\", \"[[Ridiculous Thoughts]]\", \"[[Salvation (The Cranberries song)|Salvation]]\", \"[[Free to Decide]]\", and \"[[Promises (The Cranberries song)|Promises]]\".<ref name=US />\n<br />Their fifth studio album ''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'' was released in October 2001.\n\nIn early 2009, after a six-year hiatus, the Cranberries reunited and began a North American tour followed by shows in Latin America and Europe.<ref name=\"SPIN.com\">{{cite web| url=https://www.spin.com/2009/11/cranberries-reunite-after-six-years/| title=The Cranberries Reunite After Six Years| website=Spin.com| accessdate=12 November 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Dolores\">{{cite web| url=http://www.doloresoriordan.ie/news-all.asp| title=CRANBERRIES HIT SOUTH AMERICA!/FIRST OFFICIALLY ANNOUNCED TOUR DATE FOR EUROPE!| publisher=Dolores O'Riordan| accessdate=24 December 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831111453/http://www.doloresoriordan.ie/news-all.asp| archivedate=31 August 2009}}</ref> The band recorded their sixth album ''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' in May 2011, and released it in February 2012. ''[[Something Else (The Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'', an album covering many of the band's most popular songs along with new orchestral accompaniments provided by the Irish Chamber Orchestra, was released in April 2017.<ref name=\"pitchfork3-14-2017\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/72242-listen-to-the-cranberries-new-acoustic-version-of-linger/|title=The Cranberries Announce New Acoustic Album Something Else, Share \"Linger\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> The album also included three new songs: \"The Glory\", \"Rupture\" and \"Why?.<ref name=\"SPILL\">{{cite web|url=http://spillmagazine.com/spill-album-review-cranberries-something-else/|title=Three new songs appear on this album: 'The Glory,' 'Rupture,' and 'Why.'|website=spillmagazine.com|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/cranberries-final-sessions-dolores-oriordan/|title=Something Else, which contained acoustic and orchestral takes of 10 of their songs, along with three new tracks, \"The Glory,\" \"Rupture\" and \"Why.\"|website=www.ultimateclassicrock.com|date=7 March 2018|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2018, lead singer [[Dolores O'Riordan]] was found dead of drowning in a London hotel room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/dolores-oriordan-cranberries-lead-vocalist-dies-46|title=Dolores O'Riordan: The Cranberries' Lead Vocalist Dies at 46 |website=www.grammy.com|date=16 January 2018|accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref> She had recently arrived in [[London]] for a studio mixing session on her [[D.A.R.K.]] album and to discuss the band's latest album with record label [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/20/dolores-oriordan-working-new-cranberries-album-died-says-publicist/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/dolores-oriordan-was-working-on-a-new-cranberries-album-before-her-untimely-death-36509243.html|title=The Cranberries frontwoman Dolores O\u2019Riordan was in London to discuss plans for the band\u2019s latest album when she died.|website=www.independent.ie|date=19 January 2018|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> The Cranberries confirmed in September<!-- This confirmation was announced in September, so do not change to November, thank you --> 2018 that they would not continue as a band, releasing their final album ''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' in April 2019 and disbanding afterward.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/cranberries-final-album-in-the-end|title=The Cranberries final album 'In The End' is a celebration of Dolores O'Riordan's talent|website=www.irishcentral.com|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref> Noel Hogan stated: \"the Cranberries was the four of us. We don\u2019t want to do this without Dolores. So we\u2019re going to leave it after this.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/cranberries-talk-everybody-else-is-doing-it-reissue-final-album-with-dolores-o-riordan-731376/|title=The Cranberries on Their Surprise Hit Debut and Final Album With Dolores O\u2019Riordan|first1=Richard|last1=Bienstock|first2=Richard|last2=Bienstock|date=9 October 2018|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Cranberries have sold over 40 million albums worldwide as of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cranberries.com/biography|title=Biography|website=www.cranberries.com|date=12 October 2019|accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/cranberries-new-album-4-16-19/|title=The band have sold more than 40 million albums worldwide.|website=www.bestclassicbands.com|date=16 April 2019|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/hozier-becomes-fourth-irish-artist-reach-no-1-us-22768706|title=Overall, they have sold almost 50 million albums.|website=www.hotpress.com|date=12 March 2019|accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> The band ranks as one of the best-selling alternative acts of the '90s which garnered them an [[MTV Europe Music Award]], a [[World Music Award]], an International Group nomination at [[Brit Awards]], a [[Juno Award|Juno]] nomination and a Juno Award win. The band was nominated for the [[Ivor Novello Awards]] and received an Ivor Novello Award for International Achievement. In 1998 they performed at the [[Nobel Peace Prize Concert]]. In 2016, they received a [[BMI Award]] with a Special Citation of Achievement. ''[[In the End (album)|In The End]]'' earned them a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nomination for Best Rock Album.\n\n==History==\n===Formation and early years (1989\u20131992)===\nBrothers [[Noel Hogan]] and Mike Hogan, descendants of the nineteenth-century Irish poet [[Michael Hogan (poet)|Michael Hogan]], met Fergal Lawler in the mid-1980s.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}}<ref name=\"MD95\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.moderndrummer.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/md191cs.pdf|title=Fergal Lawler|website=Modern Drummer.|year= 1995|publisher=David Frangioni|location=USA|issn=0194-4533|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408192338/https://www.moderndrummer.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/md191cs.pdf|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The young kids who grew up together in [[Limerick]], [[Ireland]], also shared their love of '80s English/[[indie music]] and were \"galvanised by punk\u2019s [[DIY ethic]]\".<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/noel-hogan-cranberries-everybody-else-interview/|title=\"It Was The Perfect Time And Place\"|last=Peacock|first=Tim|website=uDiscoverMusic.|date=19 October 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/rTfBg|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CR2019\">{{cite web|url=https://crypticrock.com/interview-noel-hogan-of-the-cranberries/|title=Interview - Noel Hogan|website=Cryptic Rock.|date=27 December 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/HYnDE|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> Lawler received his first [[drum kit]] as a Christmas present when he was about seventeen; two months later, Mike Hogan received his first [[Bass guitar|bass]] and his brother his first [[Electric guitar|guitar]].<ref name=\"MD95\"/> Niall Quinn who lived in the region already played with his own group called Hitchers and occasionally came often to share his experiences with the trio.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/> Thereafter, they were leaning towards the idea of a four piece ensemble and Quinn stayed with them.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/>\n\nIn mid-1989, brothers Mike, 16, and Noel Hogan, 18, formed The Cranberry Saw Us with drummer Fergal Lawler, 18, and singer Niall Quinn.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=21}}{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=37}} In early 1990, Quinn left them to return to his previous group, although they remained on good terms.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=22}}<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/> Despite this unexpected broke up, the three musicians became an instrumental group during several months, continuing to improve ideas and song structures of instrumental pieces.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/> Lawler and the two Hogan brothers then placed an advertisement for a female singer.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/><ref name=Programme>The Cranberries Loud & Clear World Tour Programme, \"A Timeline of the Cranberries 1989\u2013'99\", pp. 8\u201310.</ref> Subsequently, Quinn suggested to introduce the trio to a friend of his girlfriend's sister, mentioning that she was a singer-songwriter looking for a group who would compose originals.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/>\n\nOn a Sunday afternoon in mid-1990, 18-year-old [[Dolores O'Riordan]] cycled to the audition at Xeric Studios dressed in a tracksuit and with a broken [[Casio keyboard]] under her arm.<ref name=\"HP CLARCK\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/culture/ode-to-dolores-the-full-hot-press-cover-story-on-dolores-oriordan-21734931|title=Ode To Dolores|last=Clark|first=Stuart|website=HotPress.|date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/yfVZX|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\" RS BROWNE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-cranberries-final-album-interview-790271/|title=The Making of the Cranberries' Haunted Farewell|last=Browne|first=David|website=Rolling Stone.|date=7 February 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Bm4us|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> O'Riordan said of the first encounter \"''I really liked what I heard; I thought they were very nice and tight. It was a lovely potential band but they needed a singer - and direction''\".<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/><ref name=\"HP CLARCK\"/> [[Noel Hogan]] gave her a rough cassette demo incorporating chord sequences of indie-[[Jangle|jangly]] guitar sounds, then O'Riordan took home Hogan's tape and began writing lyrics and overlaying melodies which would underpin the group's future material.<ref name=\"RS BROWNE\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> Within a week she returned to the musicians with whom she sang along a rough version of \"Linger\" .<ref name=\"RS BROWNE\"/> Mike Hogan later described it as \"''we were immediately blown away, her voice was something special''\".<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/> Noel Hogan elaborated, \"''she was so small and quiet... then she opened her mouth and this amazing voice, this huge voice came out for the size of her''\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/23/713529217/the-cranberries-final-album-celebrates-the-new-beginning-dolores-o-riordan-wante?t=1575744084687&t=1586214906649|title=Music Interviews|last=Martin|first=Rachel|website=NPR.|date=23 April 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/AkyVD|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> and then acknowledged: \"''how come she\u2019s not already in a band?'' [ ... ] ''that day changed our lives''\".<ref name=\"CR2019\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> A musical relationship rapidly developed between O\u2019Riordan and Noel Hogan who had enough songs to design a demo.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/dolores-oriordan-and-the-cranberries-strange-fruit-72247/|title=The improbable rise of Ireland\u2019s biggest musical export since U2|last=Foege|first=Alec|website=Rolling Stone.|date=23 March 1995|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/TODBm|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The fledgling band recorded a four-track demo EP called ''[[Water Circle]]'', released in cassette format by local record label Xeric Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/the-cranberries-were-the-ultimate-teen-soundtrack-band/|title=The Cranberries|last=Berman|first=Judy|website=Pitchfork.|date=17 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/RHx6S|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/ce9edf12-b5c7-4acd-b008-c5760742342f|title=Water Circle release by The Cranberry Saw Us|website=MusicBrainz.|date=22 September 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/f7YeO|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1990, the group performed their first gig with O'Riordan at an hotel basement called Ruby's Club, Cruises Hotel, Limerick, performing six original songs to an audience of 60 people including three others local groups.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=25}}<ref name=\"HP CLARCK\"/> The Cranberry Saw Us moved to Xeric Recording studio and recorded ''[[Nothing Left at All]]'',{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=24}} a first commercial three-track EP released on tape in 300 copies by Xeric Records, which sold out in local record shops in Limerick within a few days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/870e3053-2561-4961-b487-be542a0817c1|title=Nothing Left at All release by The Cranberry Saw Us|website=MusicBrainz.|date=22 September 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/2HQTq|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whytes.ie/art/the-cranberries-nothing-left-at-all-1990-cassette-tape/144410/?SearchString=&LotNumSearch=&GuidePrice=&OrderBy=LH&ArtistID=&ArrangeBy=list&NumPerPage=15&offset=149|title=Nothing Left At All 1990 cassette tape|website=Whyte's.|date=30 May 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/CUhdl|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The owner of Xeric Studios, Pearse Gilmore, became their manager and provided the group with studio time to complete a demo tape which he produced.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> It featured early versions of \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\" and \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\", which were sent directly to record companies in London by Noel Hogan, determined to leave the [[Underground culture|underground circuit]] of small Irish clubs and pubs.<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/>{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=26}} [[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]] label founder [[Geoff Travis]] immediately gave his approval, although The Cranberries did not sign on his label the demo continued to earn the attention of both the UK [[History of British newspapers|press]] and record industry and sparked a bidding war between major British [[record label]]s.<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/>{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=26}}\n\nOn 18 April 1991, the group played a decisive show in their hometown at [[Shopping centres in Limerick|Jetland Center]] as part of the [[University of Limerick]]\u2019s [[RAG Week]] to 1,400 students.<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/> In attendance was record producer [[Denny Cordell]] who was then [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] for [[Island Records]], and thirty-two other A&R men who flew from [[London]].<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> Shortly thereafter, the band changed their name to \"The Cranberries\".<ref name=\" FANNING91\">{{cite web|url=https://fanningsessions.wordpress.com/2011/02/23/cork-rocks-1991/|title=Cork Rock (1991)|last=Fanning|first=Dave|website=The Fanning Sessions.|date=23 February 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/MNEB|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> ''Nothing Left at All'' began to circulate in [[UK]] with the support of John Best PR agency.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} Then, they performed their first UK tour opening for the British band [[Moose (band)|Moose]] throughout a series of three weeks.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} The Cranberries received more letters expressing interest from [[Virgin Records|Virgin]], [[EMI Records|EMI]], [[Imago Records|Imago]], [[CBS Records International|CBS]], and [[Warner Records|Warner]], which led Hogan brothers to quit their jobs.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> Eventually the group signed to a six albums deal with [[Island Records]] who won the battle.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=25-26}}{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} In mid-1991, The Cranberries headed back into the studio with Gilmore as their producer to record \"''hastily''\" their first EP ''[[Uncertain (EP)|Uncertain]]'' and created a music video for the title track, which was not released.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> Gilmore, in an incoherent gesture, made various alterations to the album's rough cuts.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=27}} 5,000 total copies of ''Uncertain'' were printed and released in October 1991 by [[Island Records]] under the Xeric name.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/3abd4cd5-08af-49bf-bb17-ecd2918847fc|title=Uncertain release by The Cranberries|website=MusicBrainz.|date=12 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/j1i8t|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The EP received poor reviews in the press and led to tension between the group and Gilmore.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=27}} By this time, Gilmore began restricting information to The Cranberries and made separate arrangements with Island\u2019s U.S branch.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> In October 1991 The Cranberries performed at [[Camden Underworld|Underworld]] in London during a UK and Ireland tour.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> Adding to this period of doubt, touring conditions and money were lacking with maximum earnings of $25 a day.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=25-26}} On 9 December 1991, The Cranberries was supposed to support [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] in [[Belfast]]'s Conor Hall, but Nirvana canceled their tour at the last moment as well as the [[List of Nirvana concerts|five remaining shows]] due to ill health of [[Kurt Cobain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livenirvana.com/concerts/cancelled.php|title=Live Nirvana Concert Chronology - Cancelled Shows|website=LiveNIRVANA.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Sq8vm|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-46509946|title=King's Hall concerts from The Beatles to Nirvana|last=Kearney|first=Joe|website=BBC.|date=12 January 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/0Cbkb|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter a difficult recording session, intended for their [[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?|first album]] on Island Records in January 1992, the band scrapped their work and fired Gilmore.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=27}}<ref name=Programme /> [[Noel Hogan]] stated \"''we didn\u2019t have a problem with each other, we had a problem with this guy''\".<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> During that time period The Cranberries toured in [[Ireland]] and the [[UK]] as opening act for TOP, getting more attention of the British press.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=28}} Subsequently, they hired [[Geoff Travis]] as their new manager,<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> The Cranberries headed back into the studio in [[Dublin]] in March 1992 to restart working on their first LP with [[Stephen Street]], who had previously worked with [[The Smiths]].{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}}<ref name=Programme /> The Cranberries began a UK and Ireland headlining tour during the last four months of 1992 to promote the subsequent release of ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]''.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} In October 1992, \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" was released in the UK, becoming ''[[Melody Maker]]'''s Single of the week.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}} In November 1992, they performed at the emblematic [[Royal Albert Hall]] supporting [[Mercury Rev|Miercury Rev]] and [[The House of Love]].{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} Between 1991 and 1993, the band also recorded several [[The Cranberries radio and television sessions|studio and live sessions]] intended for Irish and British radio and television shows, including [[2fm]]'s ''[[The Dave Fanning Show]]'' in Dublin and [[BBC Radio 1]]'s ''[[John Peel]] Show''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pastdaily.com/2018/01/15/dolores-oriordan-1991-past-daily-memorial-edition/|title=Dolores O\u2019Riordan \u2013 The Cranberries In Session \u2013 1991|last=Skene|first=Gordon|website=Past Daily.|date=15 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/bXvYW|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\" FANNING91\"/>\n\n===Mainstream success (1993\u20131995)===\n[[File:The Cranberries at Roxy Bar 1995.jpg|alt=O'Riordan onstage with a large acoustic guitar|thumb|left|upright|O'Riordan singing onstage at the height of their fame, 1995]]\nTheir first full-length album ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'' was released in March 1993.<ref name=Programme /> Neither the album nor the single gained much attention, nor did a second single, \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\".{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}} When the band embarked on a tour supporting [[Suede (band)|Suede]], they caught the attention of [[MTV]], which put their videos into heavy rotation.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}} The defining moment occurred when mid-way through the tour running order was reversed and The Cranberries replaced Suede as the tour headliners.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/remembering-dolores-o-riordan-can-you-lend-me-20-quid-and-buy-me-a-drink-1.3357191|title=Remembering Dolores O'Riordan|last=Boyd|first=Brian|website=The Irish Times.|date=16 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/6oDIv|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> During the U.S. tour, Linger received heavy rotation on college radio stations across the country.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}} Although \"Linger\" was first released in the UK in February 1993, peaking at 74, it was later re-issued in February 1994 peaking at 14. \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\", the band's first big hit, peaked at number three in Ireland and stayed on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard]] Hot 100 list for 24 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/01/16/zombie-linger-dreams-classic-cranberries-songs-following-dolores-oriordans-tragic-death-7232492/|title=Zombie, Linger, Dreams and more classic The Cranberries songs|website=metro.co.uk|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> This was followed by \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" released again in May 1994 peaking at No.&nbsp;27 on the UK charts and top 15 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard]] Hot 100 list, which helped their debut album to top both the [[UK Album Chart]] and [[Irish Albums Chart|Ireland Album Chart]] in June.<ref name=\"ILL Lynch\"/> In January 1994, Dolores injured her knee when skiing in the Swiss Alps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/9064833/Dolores-ORiordan-I-was-famous-but-I-just-felt-so-isolated.html|title=Skiing accident in Val d'Is\u00e8re|website=www.telegraph.co.uk|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> By 1994, The Cranberries world tour averaged 13,500 attendees at each performance.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}}\n\nThe group reunited with Street for ''[[No Need to Argue]]'', which was released in late 1994. It would go on to peak at No.&nbsp;6 on the US charts and eventually outsold its predecessor. Within a year it went triple platinum, spawning the number one hit \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" and the No.&nbsp;11 \"[[Ode to My Family]]\" on the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref name=\"US\" /> By March 1994, The Cranberries won the Top International Act of [[Music Week]] (UK).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/crancyclopedia/biography/|title=Top International Act|website=cranberriesworld.com|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> On 13 August 1994, during their US tour, The Cranberries performed at [[Woodstock '94|Woodstock II]] festival, [[Saugerties, New York|Saugerties]], New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1994-08-13-mn-26772-story.html|title=New Generation of Fans Flocks to Woodstock '94 |last1=J.Goldman|first1=John|last2=Braun|first2=Stephen|website=LA Times.|date=13 August 1994|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/AjEBk|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1995, the band continued to tour, and released two more singles \"[[I Can't Be with You]]\" and \"[[Ridiculous Thoughts]]\". The album went 5\u00d7 platinum in Canada, platinum in Switzerland, and 7\u00d7 platinum in the United States.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web\n |url         = https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=The_Cranberries&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25\n |title       = RIAA Certifications\n |publisher   = [[Recording Industry Association of America]]\n |accessdate  = 24 June 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6ANx0WHyD?url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=The_Cranberries&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&\n |archivedate = 2 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CRIA\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php \n |title=CRIA Certifications \n |publisher=[[Music Canada|CRIA]] \n |accessdate=24 June 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601023939/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php\n |archivedate=1 June 2009\n}}</ref><ref name=\"SWI C\">{{cite web\n| url=http://hitparade.ch/search_certifications.asp?search=The+Cranberries\n| title=SWI Certifications\n| publisher=Switzerland\n| accessdate=24 June 2008 }}</ref>\n[[File:The Cranberries, Washington, D.C., USA, 15 May 1995.jpg|thumb|right|Crowd scene before riot broke out during The Cranberries concert in Washington, D.C. 1995]]\nOn 20 February 1995, The Cranberries received a nomination at the [[Brit Awards]] in the [[Brit Award for International Group|International Group category]], at the 15th edition of the annual pop music awards in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicforstowaways.wordpress.com/2014/01/30/the-brit-awards-1995/|title=The BRIT Awards 1995|website=Music for stowaways.|date=30 January 2014|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/f1624|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ireland-at-the-brit-awards-look-back-at-every-irish-winner-and-nominee__25596/|title=Ireland at the BRIT Awards: look back at every Irish winner and nominee|date=19 January 2019|website=www.officialcharts.com|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> In mid-1995, The Cranberries had broken the American market, at that time the band was Ireland\u2019s biggest musical export since [[U2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-cranberries-have-broken-the-all-important-american-market-americans-clasped-dolores-to-their-1593543.html|title=The Cranberries have broken the all-important American market. |website=www.independent.co.uk/ceremonies|date=28 July 1995|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> On 15 May 1995, The Cranberries had planned an impromptu free acoustic set for 3,000 people at [[National Sylvan Theater]], [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]].<ref name=\"WTOP\">{{cite web|url=https://wtop.com/music/2018/01/time-cranberries-played-free-show-d-c-riot-broke/|title=The Cranberries played a free show in DC \u2014 and a riot broke out|last=Augenstein|first=Neal|website=Washington's Top News.|date=16 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/8tyIo|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\">{{cite news |first=Cesar|last=G. Soriano |authorlink=The Washington Times |title=Concert crowd hits police with rocks|url=https://i.redd.it/4kxz4xx880k21.jpg |format=broadsheet|newspaper=The Washington Times|publisher=Larry Beasley|location=United States|issn=0732-8494|page=5|date=16 May 1995 |language=english|archiveurl=https://archive.today/GRCCb|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"WTOP MP3\">{{Cite episode |title=WTOP's Neal Augenstein recalls The Cranberries in D.C|url=https://wtop.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/1CRANBERRIESnau.mp3 |access-date=11 April 2020|series=WTOP News|last=Augenstein|first=Neal|station=107.7 MHz|date=16 January 2018 |minutes=1|transcript=Top News from WTOP|transcript-url=https://podcastone.com/top-news-from-wtop?showAllEpisodes=true|language=English}}</ref> The show was orchestrated  by radio station [[WHFS (historic)|WHFS]], which had paid for the use of five U.S. [[Park police|Park Police]] officers.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> Before the show began, the organizers promptly realized how erroneous their original crowd estimates were when a frenzied crowd of over 10,000 appeared.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> The Cranberries show started 40 minutes late, while [[stage diving]] started before the first guitar note was played.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> Park Police officers established that they couldn't control the crowd and stopped the show after one song and a half.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> The crowd were told The Cranberries would not be returning and the raging crowd sparked riots throwing rocks, food and beer bottles at the Park Police officers in riot helmets, some jumped onstage and O'Riordan's acoustic guitar was stolen.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> More Police officers in riot gear came in, dozens of [[Mounted police|mounted horse patrols]] established a perimeter and cleared the south quarter of the [[Washington Monument]] grounds as a helicopter circled overhead while the fracas continued outside.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> On 23 May 1995, at London\u2019s [[Grosvenor House]], The Cranberries were nominated for Best Contemporary Song at the [[Ivor Novello Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioswissjazz.ch/en/music-database/band/24104893adafd06a6f0a84c66f4f17a9e56357/biography?app=true|title=Awards and Nominations|website=www.radioswissjazz.ch|date=30 January 2012|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>  In 1995 they performed \"[[Ode to My Family|Ode To my family]]\" at the [[World Music Awards]], winning the Award for Best Irish Recording Artists.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=20}} The Cranberries were named Best Irish Recording Artists at the 10th annual Irish Music awards, held at Dublin's Burlington Hotel.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=20}}{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}} On 23 November 1995 The Cranberries won the \"Best Song\" award for \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" at the [[1995 MTV Europe Music Awards]], beating out [[Michael Jackson]]'s \u201c[[You Are Not Alone]]\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a1398/in-depth-mtv-europe-music-awards/|title=The 1995 MTV Europe Music Awards - Le Zenith, Paris |website=www.digitalspy.com|date=11 October 2000|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}} During the ''[[No Need To Argue]]'' European tour '95, The Cranberries performed to more than 500,000 people,<ref name=\"UL\"/> with peak attendance reaching 20,000 people per night in [[United States]].<ref name=\"CSM Parney\"/>\n\n===Middle era (1996\u20132000)===\nOn 10 March 1996, The Cranberries received the Best-Selling Album Award for ''[[No Need to Argue]]'' at the 26th Annual [[Juno Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/nomination/1996-best-selling-album-foreign-or-domestic-the-cranberries/|title=Best Selling Album|website=www.junoawards.ca|date=10 March 1996|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilovelimerick.ie/the-cranberries-single-dreams/|title= Juno Award for International Album of the Year, No Need To Argue|website=www.ilovelimerick.ie|date=14 October 2016|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> The band's third album ''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'' peaked at No.&nbsp;2 in the UK and No.&nbsp;4 on the ''[[Billboard 200]]''.<ref name=\"US\" /><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web\n |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/\n |title=British Album Chart \n |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]\n |accessdate=24 June 2008 \n |df= \n}}</ref> ''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'' sells to 4 million copies in six weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/crancyclopedia/biography/|title=To The Faithful Departed sells a striking 4 million copies within six weeks|website=www.cranberriesworld.com|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> Despite favourable reviews, the album did not match the sales of ''No Need to Argue''. The album went double platinum in the US and Gold in the UK.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web\n| url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/index.asp\n| title=BPI Certifications\n| publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]\n| accessdate=24 June 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080424073628/http://www.bpi.co.uk/index.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 24 April 2008}}</ref> The first single from the album was \"[[Salvation (The Cranberries song)|Salvation]]\" which topped the Modern Rock Tracks chart.<ref name=\"US\" /> The second single from the album was \"[[Free to Decide]]\"; the single's peak in the UK was 33<ref name=\"UK\" /> and placing on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].In September 1996, The Cranberries' video for \"Salvation\" was nominated for a MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1996/mtvvmas.htm|title=1996 MTV Video Music Awards|website=Rock on the Net.|date=4 September 1996|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/W0rO|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/mtv-vmas-1996-489.html|title=MTV VMAs 1996|website=Awards and Shows.|date=15 September 1996|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/1HOuC|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In November 1996 \"[[When You're Gone (Cranberries song)|When You're Gone]]\" was released as a single in the United States, peaking at 22 on the Hot 100.<ref name=\"US\" /> In late 1996, the group cancelled their Australian and European tour, O'Riordan re-injured her knee during a concert in [[Cairns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/1996/6/9/19247343/lead-singer-s-knee-injury-forces-cancellation-of-tour|title=Lead Singer's Knee Injury Forces Cancellation of Tour|website=www.deseret.com|date=9 June 1996|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:The Cranberries, Palalido, Italy, April 20, 1999.jpg|thumb|left|The Cranberries performing in Milan, 1999]]\nOn 9 March 1997, [[Bruce Fairbairn]] and The Cranberries were nominees at the [[Juno Award]]s for their work on \"[[Free to Decide]]\" and \"[[When You're Gone (Cranberries song)|When You're Gone]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/nomination/1997-producer-of-the-year-bruce-fairbairn-the-cranberries-co-producers/|title=Producer of the Year 1997|website=www.junoawards.ca|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> The band received an [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for International Achievement, on 19 May 1997, at London\u2019s [[Grosvenor House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicforstowaways.wordpress.com/2018/11/08/ivor-novello-awards-the-1990s/|title=Ivor Novello Awards 1997|website=www.musicforstowaways.wordpress.com|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hessomedia.com/final-album-end-cranberries-charts-10/|title=they have won the Ivor Novello Award for International Achievement.|website=www.hessomedia.com|date=3 May 2019|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 November 1998 [[Dolores O'Riordan]] and Fergal Lawler made an appearance at the [[1998 MTV Europe Music Awards]] in [[Milan]] and presented the award for best song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/crancyclopedia/biography/|title=The band is invited to present the award for Best Song at the MTV European Music Awards|website=cranberriesworld.com|date=12 November 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-mtv-cranberries-106074501.html|title=The Cranberries at the MTV Awards ceremony|website=www.alamy.com|date=12 November 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref> The band played \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\", \"Promises\" and \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\" at [[Nobel Peace Prize Concert|The Nobel Peace Prize Concert]] 1998, on 11 December at [[Oslo Spektrum]], Oslo, [[Norway]]. \"Promises\" is performed live for the first time, four months before the release of the album ''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1427569/alanis-morissette-cranberries-tapped-for-nobel-concert/|title=Cranberries Tapped For Nobel Concert |website=www.mtv.com|date=10 December 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/live/promo-performances/nobel-peace-prize-concert/|title=Nobel Peace Prize Concert  |website=cranberriesworld.com|date=10 December 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/1998/summary/|title=The Nobel Peace Prize 1998|website=www.nobelprize.org|date=16 October 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, The Cranberries released ''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]''. The first single \"Promises\" was released in February. \"Promises\" would be the only single from the album to chart in the US and last single before their hiatus.<ref name=\"US\" /> The album peaked at 7 in the UK and 13 in the US<ref name=\"US\" /><ref name=\"UK\" /> and was certified gold in the US.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> The second single from the album was \"[[Animal Instinct (Cranberries song)|Animal Instinct]]\", which didn't chart in the UK, although it did chart in France, Austria and many others.<ref name=\"IRE\">{{cite web\n| url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Cranberries&titel=Animal+Instinct&cat=s\n| title=Chart\n| website=Lescharts.com\n| accessdate=24 June 2008 }}</ref> The third and fourth singles were \"Just My Imagination\" and \"You & Me\", respectively. The band had a guest appearance on popular television series ''[[Charmed]]'', performing \"[[Just My Imagination (Cranberries song)|Just My Imagination]]\" on the fifth episode of the second season, \"[[Charmed (season 2)#Episode list|She's a Man, Baby, a Man!]]\". The group started a world tour in April 1999 and it finished in July 2000. The group partnered with Ticketmaster.com to be the first artists to sell tickets for a national tour exclusively online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1999/biz/news/tix-selling-quick-for-ticketmaster-online-1117493279/|title=Tix selling quick for Ticketmaster Online|website=variety.com|date=15 April 1999 |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref> It was the biggest and most successful tour of the Cranberries' career.<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\">{{cite magazine |last=Sexton|first=Paul|date=27 October 2001|title=Cranberries 'Wake' To New Beginning |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=kBEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=the+cranberries&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIjYyQpMrnAhURxIUKHdoXA7oQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|magazine=Billboard |location=USA|volume=113|issue=43|page=14|publisher=Nielsen Business Media Inc.|issn=0006-2510|url-status=live|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> The tour brought them back to Ireland for their first date since May 2000. They performed at [[Millstreet]] in [[County Cork]]. As the tour rolled on, the band released ''Bury The Hatchet&nbsp;\u2013 The Complete Sessions'', a double CD featuring B-sides as well as live tracks taken from a show in Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishmusicdaily.com/cranberries-no-need-to-argue|title=Cranberries' Most Successful Tour|website=www.irishmusicdaily.com|date=1 November 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Later years (2001\u20132003)===\nIn October 2001, the album ''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'' was released.<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\"/> The band's old producer [[Stephen Street]] had returned and produced their new music video.<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\"/> The album peaked at 46 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],<ref name=\"US\" /> No. 2 on Spanish, Italian and French album charts. It went to No. 8 in Canada's Billboard Chart and reached No. 61 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pure-music.co.uk/wake-up-and-smell-the-coffee-album-cover/|title=\"Wake Up And Smell The Coffee\" is the fifth studio album released by Irish alternative rock band The Cranberries.|website=www.pure-music.co.uk|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"UK\" /> The first single released from the album was \"[[Analyse (Cranberries song)|Analyse]]\", which charted in the US Adult Top 40 at a peak of 26.<ref name=\"US\" /><ref name=\"UK\" /> In January 2002, they released the second single \"[[Time Is Ticking Out]]\", and some months later another one, \"This Is the Day\".\nThe Cranberries was managed by ''Timeless Management'' in [[London]].<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\"/>\n\nThe following year a greatest hits album was released entitled ''[[Stars&nbsp;\u2013 The Best of 1992\u20132002]]'' which was released alongside an [[Stars - The Best of 1992 - 2002 (DVD)|eponymous DVD]] of [[music video]]s. The album peaked in the UK at 20.<ref name=\"UK\" /> The song \"[[Stars (The Cranberries song)|Stars]]\" was released as a single from that album. They started a European tour in mid-October 2002 and ended in December.\n\nIn January 2003, following advice from their legal advisors, The Cranberries parted ways with record [[MCA Records|label MCA]], due to the band's dissatisfaction with the ''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'''s promotion.<ref name=\"BB MCA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/72598/cranberries-terminate-mca-contract|title=Cranberries Terminate MCA Contract|website=Billboard.|date=22 January 2003|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/PwZxH|archivedate=13 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HP MCA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/cranberries-split-from-mca-2634515|title=Cranberries split from MCA|website=Hot Press.|date=21 January 2003|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/eRASH|archivedate=13 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> [[Noel Hogan]] observed \"''with little effort from our label, we have been pleased to see top-10 sales in many countries''\".<ref name=\"BB MCA\"/> Despite comments from MCA regarding that the album didn't reach the [[Billboard 200]]'s top 30, the 2002 concerts drew an average audience of 10,000 people, with many of the dates selling-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/34thanks-to-our-incredibly-supportive-fans-we-say-fuck-em34-2613266|title=We say 'fuck 'em' - Thanks to our incredibly supportive fans|website=Hot Press.|date=19 September 2002|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/53kr4|archivedate=13 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HP MCA\"/> O'Riordan told ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'': \"''since we were signed in 1991 by Island Records, we have gradually seen our label dissolve from a pioneering independent spirited label into a corporate monolith that completely lost touch with the group's creative vision''\".<ref name=\"BB MCA\"/> The Cranberries signed in 1991 with [[Island Records]] America which was transferred to [[MCA Records|MCA]] in 2000 following a contract renegotiation.<ref name=\"HP MCA\"/><ref name=\"BB MCA\"/>\n\nAt the end of February 2003, the Cranberries started working with [[Stephen Street]] and debuted their work for the first time in [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland, on 29 May 2003 performing the songs \"Astral Projection\" and \"In it Together\".<ref name=\"IT2007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/dolores-stories-1.1295395|title=Dolores stories|website=Irish Times.|date=27 April 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/HlPLA/mQRyg|archivedate=27 April 2007|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolesmag.com/article-1252-The-Cranberries-Tomorrow.html|title=The Cranberries \"Roses\"|website=Idoles Mag.|date=31 January 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/DDMMd|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> In September 2003, the band announced they were taking some time to pursue individual careers, as well as concentrate on family, and scrapped sessions for a sixth studio release.<ref name=\"HP 2003\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotpress.com/The-Cranberries/news/The-Cranberries-are-NOT-going-to-split/2679953.html|title=The Cranberries are NOT going to split|author=The Hot Press Newsdesk|website=Hot Press.|date=17 September 2003|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/vbexN|archivedate=9 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Initially, a two-year sabbatical was confirmed, while O'Riordan assured that the group would just take a hiatus, she said \"''we've been together for 13 years; it's a much needed break. It was getting predictable and lacking in a challenge; time to experiment''\".<ref name=\"HP 2003\"/> Althought a spokesperson for The Cranberries announced a \"temporary shutdown in activities\", the four members remained on good terms and in regular contact with each other.<ref name=\"HP 2003\"/>\n\nBetween 1994 and 2003, The Cranberries undertook several world tours and performed in front of crowds of 10,000 to 20,000 each night.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}}<ref name=\"UL\"/><ref name=\"CSM Parney\">{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1995/0811/11111.html|title=The Cranberries Prove Red Hot on Beginning Leg of US Tour|last=Leigh Parney|first=Lisa|website=The Christian Science Monitor.|date=11 August 1995|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/4ABox|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Hiatus and solo careers (2004\u20132008)===\n[[File:Dolores O'Riordan.jpg|alt=O'Riordan singing with a guitarist behind her|thumb|O'Riordan singing solo, 2007]]\n[[Dolores O'Riordan]] started collaborating with other musicians in 2004 before launching her solo career with the album ''[[Are You Listening? (Dolores O'Riordan album)|Are You Listening?]]'' in 2007 and a world tour, following it with ''[[No Baggage]]'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Ferguson|first=Tom|date=8 August 2009|title=Baggage Packed |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=lCUF-Ml_lBYC&pg=PT25&dq=dolores+o%27riordan+no+baggage+are+you+listening+world+tour+2007&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwif677VxePoAhW66uAKHUMIAOAQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q&f=false|magazine=Billboard |location=USA|volume=121|issue=31|page=26|publisher=Nielsen Business Media Inc.|issn=0006-2510|url-status=live|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/cranberries-dolores-oriordan-dies-46/|title=The Cranberries\u2019 Vocalist Dolores O\u2019Riordan|last=Peacock|first=Tim|website=uDiscoverMusic|date=15 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/u7z33|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockhermag.com/index.php/2007/05/16/dolores-oriordan-tour-dates-formally-of-the-cranberries/|title=North America 2007|website=Rockher Mag.|date=15 May 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20T9F|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Dolores O'Riordan performed \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\" in the 2006 movie [[Click (2006 film)|''Click'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0389860/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Click (2006) Full Cast & Crew|website=IMDB.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/c8Ncf|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Noel Hogan]] started a new project called [[Mono Band]], writing all instrumentation in his own personal studio and developing a \"new way of working\" with programmer Matt Vaughan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/life-after-cranberries-neil-hogan-launches-monoband-2764643|title=Neil Hogan launches Monoband|website=Hot Press.|date=12 November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/mDMq3|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IR2004\">{{cite web|url=https://irishrockers.com/artistView.php?artist=Mono%20Band|title=About Mono Band|website=IrishRockers.com|date=1 November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/qWUhs/mDMq3|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IT2007\"/> The project, whose first full-length self-titled album saw a limited release in 2005, also featured diverse guest musicians as [[Oxford]] singer-songwriter [[Richard Walters (singer-songwriter)|Richard Walters]].<ref name=\"IR2004\"/> Subsequently, Hogan decided to work mainly with Richard Walters, then Mono Band became [[Arkitekt]] whose two EP  were released in 2007 and 2009.<ref name=\"HP2007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/mono-band-change-name-3876248|title=Mono Band change name|website=Hot Press.|date=27 April 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/O0ni8|archivedate=12 July 2007|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishmusicdb.com/a/arkitekt/band_biography.htm|title=Arkitekt - biography|website=Irish Music DB.|date=1 November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/ulvmW|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://irishrockers.com/artistView.php?id=649|title=Arkitekt|website=IrishRockers.com|date=31 August 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/mQRyg|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> He has also been working as a producer with Supermodel Twins, from his native Limerick and Remma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingtunes.com/supermodeltwins|title=Supermodel Twins|website=Breakingtunes.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/q1Q8T|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishmusicdb.com/r/remma/band_singles.htm|title=Remma - band - singles|website=Irish Music DB.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/iuyjw|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, Mike Hogan and his wife Siobh\u00e1n opened a [[caf\u00e9]] called ''The Sage Caf\u00e9'', on Catherine Street in the heart of [[Limerick City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilovelimerick.ie/business-directory-2/the-sage-cafe/|title=Business Name: The Sage Caf\u00e9|last=Maher|first=Conor|website=I Love Limerick.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/wZOYe|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The award-winning caf\u00e9 closed on 25 September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.limerickpost.ie/2017/09/25/limerick-sage-cafe-closes/|title=Limerick Sage Cafe closes|date=25 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/fJx7w|archivedate=12 July 2007|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Mike Hogan also played bass with [[Mono Band]].<ref name=\"IT2007\"/>\n\nFergal Lawler was a member of The Low Network, whose first album was released in 2007.<ref name=\"IT2007\"/><ref name=\"HP2007\"/> He has also worked with Walter Mitty and the Realist as well as Last Days of Death Country as both producer and musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockandrollreport.com/the-rock-and-roll-report-band-of-the-week-is-walter-mitty-the-realists/|title=Walter Mitty & The Realists|last=Boudreau|first=Mark|website=The Rock and Roll Report.|date=20 October 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/OtR1R|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingtunes.com/lastdaysofdeathcountry|title=Last Days Of Death Country|website=Breakingtunes.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/kvEi0|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reunion and ''Roses'' (2009\u20132015)===\nThe Cranberries reunited in January 2009 to celebrate O'Riordan becoming an Honorary Patron<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|title=The Cranberries|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/apr/02/the-cranberries-review|date=2 April 2010|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Allison|last=Bray|title=Why it's all smelling of 'Roses' for the Cranberries|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/why-its-all-smelling-of-roses-for-the-cranberries-26824540.html|newspaper=[[Independent.ie]]|date=23 February 2012}}</ref> of [[University Philosophical Society (Trinity College, Dublin)]]. The group indicated at the time that this did not signify an official reunion, but on 25 August 2009, in anticipation of the release of ''[[No Baggage]]'', O'Riordan announced that the Cranberries would be reuniting for a North American and European tour.<ref>[http://www.ianaaron.eu/?p=11250] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720163119/http://www.ianaaron.eu/?p=11250|date=20 July 2011}}</ref> O'Riordan indicated that the band would be playing songs from her solo albums and a lot of the Cranberries' classic hits as well as some new group compositions.\n[[File:The Cranberries Live @ Montreal (8375953017).jpg|alt=The band onstage|thumb|The Cranberries reformed in 2012, from left to right: Fergal Lawler, Dolores O'Riordan, and Mike Hogan (Noel Hogan off camera)]]\nAt this point of their career, The Cranberries were managed by Danny Goldberg, former [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and [[Kurt Cobain]] manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternativenation.net/clone/cranberries-dolores-oriordan-revealed-avoided-kurt-cobains-fate-eerie-interview/|title=Late Cranberries singer Dolores O\u2019Riordan discussed Kurt Cobain|first=Brett|last=Buchanan|website=www.alternativenation.net|date=18 January 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/mMv0I|archivedate=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citizen.org/about/person/danny-goldberg/|title=Danny Goldberg Public Citizen Inc.|website=www.citizen.org|date=15 January 2010|archiveurl=https://archive.today/nwrW3|archivedate=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/roses-mw0002278143/credits|title=The Cranberries, Danny Goldberg Management|website=www.allmusic.com|date=4 February 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624032244/https://www.allmusic.com/album/roses-mw0002278143/credits|archivedate=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref> In 2011, the actual ''[[Water Circle]]'' demo tape emerged, widely assumed to be the first appearance of The Cranberries with the vocal of [[Dolores O'Riordan]]. A private collector from [[United States]] submitted the bid to US$1499.95 via [[eBay]] store; the offer was eclipsed later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lyricshall.com/albums/The+Cranberries/Water+Circle+EP/|title=Water Circle EP The Cranberries|website=Lyricshall.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/wCb8e|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618025659/https://www.ebay.com/itm/350154208726?hash=item5186d135d6 |title=The Cranberries Water Circle 1990 first demo tape RARE |author= eBay user \"retro*dream\" |date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Cranberries recorded ''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' at the [[Metalworks Studios]] in [[Mississauga]], Canada, from 18 April<ref name=\"cranberries.com\">[http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#165] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721084220/http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#165|date=21 July 2011}}</ref> to 15 May<ref>{{cite tweet|user=noelhogan2|author-link=Noel Hogan|number=69889310895243264|date=15 May 2011|title=Okay, that's it. Album No.&nbsp;6 recorded, everyone is great spirits after listening. On to London for strings & Steve to mix it after that|accessdate=15 January 2018}}{{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref> 2011 with Stephen Street,<ref name=\"cranberries.com\"/> who previously collaborated with the band on their first, second and fifth albums. The Cranberries worked on 15&nbsp;tracks during the ''Roses'' session, although not all were included on the album.<ref>[http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#166]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721084220/http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#166|date=21 July 2011}}</ref> ''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' was released on 27 February 2012.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cranberries.com/#roses|title=The Cranberries: ''Roses''|website=Cranberries.com|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> The sixth studio album ''Roses'' peaked at 51 on the [[Billboard 200]] chart and had numerous position in Billboard charts as No. 4 on [[Independent Albums]] chart, No. 6 on [[Canadian Albums Chart|Canadian Albums chart]], No. 9 on Alternative Albums chart, No. 10 on Rock Albums chart and No. 20 on Tastmaker Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/2012/03/08/roses-on-the-billboard-charts/|title=\"Roses\" on the Billboard charts.|website=cranberriesworld.com|date=8 March 2012|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February 2012 The Cranberries returned to the stage of the [[Teatro Ariston|Ariston Theatre]] where they presented their new single \"Tomorrow\" in Sanremo at the 62nd [[Sanremo Music Festival|Song Festival di Sanremo]], Italy. They performed \"Tomorrow\" and \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\", having been invited on more than one occasion to the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.melodicamente.com/sanremo-2012-cranberries-ospiti-finale/|title=Sanremo 2012: Cranberries|website=www.melodicamente.com|date=19 February 2012|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2013, The Cranberries album designer [[Storm Thorgerson]] died. The English graphic designer, mainly influenced by surrealism, designed ''Bury The Hatchet'' and ''Wake Up And Smell The Coffee''. Thorgerson also created artworks for these two album\u2019s singles and \u201c[[Beneath the Skin \u2013 Live in Paris|Beneath The Skin]]\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/arts/music/storm-thorgerson-69-pink-floyd-album-cover-artist-dies.html|title=Storm Thorgerson, Album Designer, Dies at 69|first=Bruce|last=Weber|website=NY Times.|date=20 April 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102221535/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/arts/music/storm-thorgerson-69-pink-floyd-album-cover-artist-dies.html|archivedate=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawsons.co.uk/blog/legendary-album-artwork-designer-storm-thorgerson-passes-away|title=Legendary Album Artwork Designer Storm Thorgerson Has Died|website=Dawsons.|date=20 April 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514162342/https://www.dawsons.co.uk/blog/legendary-album-artwork-designer-storm-thorgerson-passes-away|archivedate=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nO'Riordan started legal proceedings against [[Noel Hogan]] in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Owens|first=Alan|title=Cranberries stars could face off in the High Court|url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/what-s-on/arts-entertainment/music/cranberries-stars-could-face-off-in-the-high-court-1-5621794|work=Limerick Leader|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref> The case was struck out in July 2015 and the cause was not divulged.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/news/local-news/111394/Dolores-O-Riordan-due-in-court.html| title=Dolores O\u2019Riordan due in court over air rage incident | work=Limerick Leader| accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nO'Riordan began recording new material with [[D.A.R.K.]] in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jetlagnyc.blogspot.com/search/label/info| title=About Jetlag NYC|website=Jetlagnyc.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n\n===O'Riordan's death, ''In the End'' and disbandment (2016\u20132019)===\n[[File:Dolores O'Riordan, The Cranberries, Bospop, 2016.jpeg|thumb|left|upright|O'Riordan performing during The Cranberries Summer Tour 2016]]\nIn October 2016, The Cranberries received a [[BMI Award]] in [[London]] for three million radio plays in the [[United States]] of their single \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" taken from their [[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?|debut studio album]].<ref name=\"ILL Lynch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ilovelimerick.ie/the-cranberries-single-dreams/|title=Dreams reaches 3mill radio plays in USA|last=Lynch|first=Richard|website=I Love Limerick.|date=14 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/XnDIw|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"UM2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umusic.ca/press-releases/the-cranberries-release-everybody-else-is-doing-it-so-why-cant-we-25th-anniversary-box-set-out-october-19/|title=Broadcast Music, Inc (BMI) Award|website=Umusic.|date=30 August 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/lmQYt|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The award had been presented with a special citation of achievement.<ref name=\"ILL Lynch\"/><ref name=\"UM2018\"/>\n\nA new acoustic Cranberries album titled ''[[Something Else (Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'' was released on 28 April 2017, through [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]].<ref name=\"pitchfork3-14-2017\" /> ''[[Something Else (Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'' featured orchestral arrangements of prior releases, re-recorded in 2016 acoustically with the [[Irish Chamber Orchestra]], and three new songs : \"The Glory\", \"Why\", and \"Rupture\".<ref name=\"SPILL\"/>\n\nWith the release of the new album, the group announced a tour which was to include dates in Europe, parts of the UK, and North America. The shows were scheduled in smaller venues, with live orchestral accompaniment. However, in May 2017, shortly into the European tour, The Cranberries had to cancel the remainder of the European dates due to O'Riordan's health, with the band's website citing \"medical reasons associated with a back problem\".<ref name=BBCobituary>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42702826|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Dolores O'Riordan: Voice of a rebel|date=16 January 2018}}</ref> The North American tour dates were cancelled in July when her recovery had not progressed enough for her to participate.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cranberries \u2013 Maison Symphonique, Montr\u00e9al \u2013 Tickets|url=https://www.greenland.ca/event/view/the-cranberries-maison-symphonique-montreal-2017-09-23-tickets-1619|website=Greenland.ca|accessdate=7 October 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2018, O'Riordan died unexpectedly in London, England.<ref name=RTE15jan2018>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/0115/933523-dolores-oriordan-dies-suddenly-in-london|title=Dolores O'Riordan suddenly dies in London|work=RTE news|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref> The inquest into her death was adjourned until 3 April while the coroner awaited the results of \"various tests\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-42745624|title=Dolores O'Riordan inquest awaits tests|date=2018|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> On 6 September 2018, it was ruled that she had [[drowned]] in her hotel room's [[bathtub]] due to sedation by [[alcohol poisoning]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-45434898|title=Cranberries singer O'Riordan died by drowning|date=2018-09-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-09-06|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March 2018, the band announced they were releasing a special newly remastered 25th anniversary edition of their debut album ''Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We'', with previously unreleased material as well as other bonus material from the time of the album. However, with O'Riordan's death it was delayed until 19 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheCranberries/posts/10155531977667106|title=The Cranberries \u2013 Posts|publisher=[[Facebook]]|date=7 March 2018|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref> The band also decided to complete their new album underway at the time O'Riordan died, for which she had already recorded the vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cranberries.com/site/|title=The Cranberries \u2013 Home|accessdate=8 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311061823/http://www.cranberries.com/site/|archive-date=11 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Noel Hogan confirmed the Cranberries would not be continuing as a band, and their final album will be called ''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' stating: \"We will do this album and then that will be it. No one wants to do this without Dolores...<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-cranberries-open-up-about-the-last-days-of-singer-dolores-o-riordan-she-was-on-a-roll__24108/|title=\"She was on a roll\": The Cranberries on the last days of Dolores O\u2019Riordan|website=Officialcharts.com|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref> So there\u2019s a song called 'In the End', it\u2019s the last song on the album, and it just kind of summed up the whole album and the band. Because it\u2019s definitely the end of it for us. So we\u2019ve called it that.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> On 15 January 2019, one year after O'Riordan's death, the band released the first single from ''In the End'', called \"All Over Now\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnewsnet.com/2019/01/the-cranberries-share-first-single-all-over-now-from-final-album-in-the-end.html|title=The Cranberries share first single \u2013 \"All Over Now\" \u2013 from final album, In The End|website=Music News Net}}</ref> The Cranberries released their 8th and final album ''[[In the End (album)|In The End]]'' on 26 April 2019. The album peaked at No. 8 in [[Germany]], No. 5 in [[France]], No. 4 in [[Italy]], No. 3 in [[Ireland]] and charted in the Top 10 of the [[UK Albums Chart|UK Official Charts]]. ''In The End'' went to No. 7 on the Billboard [[Independent Albums]] chart and No. 10 on the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Top Alternative Albums chart<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cranberries.com/news/48-in-the-end-chart-positions-so-far|title=In The End chart positions so far...|website=www.cranberries.com|date=4 May 2018|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> The band released the single \"Wake Me When It's Over\" on 19 June 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnewsnet.com/2019/03/music-news-often-bands-aspire-to-be-timeless-or-to-have-a-sound-that-transcends-the-whims-of-musical-fashion-the-cranberr.html|title=THE CRANBERRIES RELEASE SINGLE \"WAKE ME WHEN IT'S OVER\", NEW \"IN THE END\" ALBUM OUT 4/26/19|website=Music News Net}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2019, [[Noel Hogan]], Mike Hogan and Fergal Lawler were conferred with [[honorary doctorate]]s by [[University of Limerick]] (UL). The posthumous award was presented to Eileen O'Riordan, mother of the band's lead singer [[Dolores O'Riordan]]. They were all presented with an Honorary Doctorate of Letters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/the-cranberries-honorary-doctorate-university-of-limerick/|title=The Cranberries will receive an honorary doctorate from University of Limerick|date=15 January 2019|website=irishcentral|accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Post-disbandment (mid-2019\u2013present)===\n[[Saint Sister]], a duo from [[Northern Ireland]], performed an acapella rendition of the song \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" at [[Lyra McKee]]'s funeral in Belfast,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/live-lyra-mckee-funeral-belfast-14545166|title=Lyra McKee funeral: Updates as loved ones pay moving tribute to murdered journalist|website=Daily Mirror|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> who was murdered by the [[Real Irish Republican Army|New IRA]] in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-479854696|title=Lyra McKee murder: Journalist shot dead during Derry rioting|website=www.bbc.com|date=19 April 2019|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nNoel Hogan joined [[Kodaline]] on stage on 1 September 2019, at the [[Electric Picnic|Electric Picnic Festival]] in [[Stradbally]], [[Ireland]], to play \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" in tribute to [[Dolores O'Riordan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonmusic.co.uk/news/electric-picnic-2019-ends-with-explosive-performances-from-florence-johnny-marr-more|title=Kodaline and Hogan tore through an stirring version of 'Zombie'|website=www.eonmusic.co.uk|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe music video restoration campaign of the entire catalogue of The Cranberries on [[YouTube]] was launched on 3 October 2019, twenty-five years after the release of the album ''[[No Need to Argue]]'', with the debut of an early \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" concert performance filmed in 1994 at [[London Astoria|London's Astoria]], remastered in high definition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/video-cranberries-zombie-youtube/|title= Irish band\u2019s catalogue-spanning video restoration campaign|website=www.udiscovermusic.com|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" is performed seven months before the song was released as a single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/cranberries-zombie-live-video-893659/|title= Watch the Cranberries Tear Through Early Version of 'Zombie' |website=www.rollingstone.com|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-cranberries-official-music-videos-to-be-released-in-remastered-high-definition-video-exclusively-on-youtube-300929371.html|title=official \"Zombie\" video's newly remastered 4K HD version|website=www.prnewswire.com|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, in an interview for ''Rock Art Fashion'', Fergal Lawler commented that the band would release a remastered edition of their album ''[[No Need to Argue]]'' as part of a 25th anniversary box set.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rockartfashion.net/2019/04/28/in-the-end-the-final-album-of-the-cranberries-interview-with-fergal-lawler/#English-Version|title=\"In The End\", the final album|website=Rock Art Fashion.|date=28 April 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/aujr9|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 November 2019, The Cranberries' final album ''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' has been nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]] at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/cranberries|title=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|website=www.grammy.com|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2019/1120/1094090-the-cranberries-among-grammy-award-nominees/|title=The Cranberries among Grammy Award nominees|website=www.rte.ie|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2020, the official music video for \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" became the first song by an Irish band to reach over one billion views on [[Youtube]], becoming the third video from the 1990s, and the sixth from the [[20th century]], to reach the milestone on the video streaming service.<ref name=\"RTE Crowley\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2020/0418/1132342-the-cranberries-join-youtubes-billion-hall-of-fame/|title=The Cranberries join YouTube's billion Hall of Fame |last=Crowley|first=Caroline|website=RTE.|date=18 April 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/PbfTN|archivedate=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nova.ie/the-cranberries-zombie-video-hits-1-billion-views-177630/|title=The Cranberries \"Zombie\" Video Hits 1 Billion Views|last=Drieberg|first=Clint|website=Nova.ie|date=18 April 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Cu4uK|archivedate=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> The Cranberries now joined a club of artists to reach this landmark including [[Guns N\u2019 Roses]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and [[A-ha]].<ref name=\"RTE Crowley\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.limerickleader.ie/news/home/535935/we-are-sure-dolores-has-a-big-proud-smile-on-her-face-limericks-most-famous-group-smashbillion-landmark.html|title=\"We are sure Dolores has a big, proud smile on her face\"|last=Fitzgerald|first=Aine|website=Limerick Leader.|date=18 April 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Mtq58|archivedate=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\n[[File:Noel-Hogan.jpg|alt=Hogan looking to the camera|thumb|upright|Co-founder and guitarist Noel Hogan has co-written many of the band's songs.]]\nTheir music has been likened [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] and [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]].<ref>{{cite web |first=J.D. |last=Considine |title=There's no disputing the power and emotion in Cranberries' mournful melodies |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-10-04/features/1994277164_1_oriordan-zombie-aow |work=Baltimoresun |date= 4 October 1994|accessdate= 1 February 2017}}</ref> O'Riordan stated her singing style incorporating yodelling was inspired by her father who used to sing \"The Lonesome Cattle Call\": \"I just kept with my father all the time, just copying him and eventually I learned how to do it. Then over the years there were artists like Sin\u00e9ad O\u2019Connor and Siouxsie from Siouxsie and the Banshees and even Peter Harvey was doing it. It was something that you could work into The Cranberries' format because a lot of that was used in religious Irish music\".<ref name=\"PM BRODSKY\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/the-cranberries.html |title=The Cranberries Talk 25th Anniversary, '90s Nostalgia|first=Rachel |last=Brodsky |work=Pastemagazine. |date=28 April 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/P5Vf6|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> O'Riordan was influenced by [[Gregorian chant]], Irish folk music, classical piano, listening to [[Duran Duran]], [[The Cure]], [[Depeche Mode]], and [[The Smiths]].{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=23}}<ref name=\"PM BRODSKY\"/> Lawler, Mike and Noel Hogan, were inspired by [[The Cure]],<ref name=\"MD95\"/> [[Joy Division]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> [[Echo & the Bunnymen]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> [[The Clash]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> and [[The Smiths]].<ref name=\"MD95\"/> Noel Hogan stressed that at their beginnings, \"All these roads led to [[The Smiths]], who became very big in our lives later on.\"<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/cranberries-25th-everybody-else/|title=25th anniversary edition of \"Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can\u2019t We?\"|last=Peacock|first=Tim|website=uDiscoverMusic.|date=30 August 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/9OM2u|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n'''Former'''\n*Niall Quinn \u2013 lead vocals, rhythm guitar (1989\u20131990)\n* Mike Hogan&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] (1989\u20132003, 2009\u20132019)\n* [[Noel Hogan]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead guitar|lead and occasional rhythm guitar]], backing vocals (1989\u20132003, 2009\u20132019)\n* Fergal Lawler&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]] (1989\u20132003, 2009\u20132019)\n* [[Dolores O'Riordan]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Singing|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar|rhythm and occasional lead guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]]s (1990\u20132003, 2009\u20132018; died 2018)\n\n'''Touring musicians'''\n* Russell Burton&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards, rhythm guitar (1996\u20132003, 2012)\n* [[Steve DeMarchi]]&nbsp;\u2013 rhythm guitar, backing vocals (1996\u20132003)\n* [[Denny DeMarchi]]&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards, rhythm guitar, backing vocals (2009\u20132011)\n* Johanna Cranitch&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals (2012\u20132017)\n* Ol\u00e9 Koretsky&nbsp;\u2013  rhythm guitar (2017)\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|The Cranberries discography}}\n'''Studio albums'''\n*''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'' (1993)\n*''[[No Need to Argue]]'' (1994)\n*''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Something Else (The Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'' (2017)\n*''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Reisfeld|first=Randi|year=1996|title=This is the sound : the best of alternative rock|language=English|location=New York|edition=1st|editor-last=Paperbacks ed.|editor-first=Aladdin|publisher=Aladdin Paperbacks|publication-date=1996|pages=[https://archive.org/details/thisissoundb00reis/page/18 18-33]|url=https://archive.org/details/thisissoundb00reis|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0-689-80670-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Rees|first1=Dafydd|last2=Crampton|first2=Luke|year=1996|title=Rock stars encyclopedia|language=English|location=New York|edition=2nd|editor-last=rev|editor-first=New|publisher=DK Pub.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/rockstarsencyclo00rees/page/248 248-249]|url=https://archive.org/details/rockstarsencyclo00rees|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0-789-44613-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bianco|first1=David P.|last2=Knight|first2=Judson|year=1998|title=Parents aren't supposed to like it : rock & other pop musicians of today|volume=Vol. 1|language=English|location=Detroit|edition=1st|editor-last=Bianco|editor-first=David P.|publisher=U X L|publication-date=1998|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780787617325/page/37 37-41]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780787617325|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0-787-61732-5|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q483810|c=category:The Cranberries|n=no|wikt=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|b=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|q=no}}\n*{{Official website}}\n* {{Curlie|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/C/Cranberries%2C_The/}}\n* [https://www.npr.org/event/music/147191308/the-cranberries-tiny-desk-concert The Cranberries] [[Tiny Desk Concerts]] by [[National Public Radio]] (23 February 2012)\n\n{{The Cranberries|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Dolores O'Riordan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cranberries, The}}\n[[Category:The Cranberries| ]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Irish alternative rock groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2003]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Limerick (city)]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:Irish indie pop groups]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:2003 disestablishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for International Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Cooking Vinyl artists]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:Downtown Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the rock band|the plant species|Cranberry|other uses|Cranberry (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Irish rock band}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = The Cranberries\n| image = The Cranberries en Barcelona 8.jpg\n| alt = Noel Hogan holding a guitar and Dolores O'Riordan singing into a microphone\n| caption = The Cranberries, guitarist [[Noel Hogan]] and lead singer [[Dolores O'Riordan]] in [[Barcelona]], 2010\n| alias = The Cranberry Saw Us<br/>(1989\u20131990)\n| landscape = yes\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Limerick]], Ireland\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Irish folk]]}}\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[post-punk]]\n}}\n| years_active = {{flatlist|\n* 1989\u20132003\n* 2009\u20132019<ref name=\"officialcharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-cranberries-open-up-about-the-last-days-of-singer-dolores-o-riordan-she-was-on-a-roll__24108/|title=\"She was on a roll\": The Cranberries open up about the last days of singer Dolores O'Riordan|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Xeric\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Downtown Records|Downtown]]\n* [[Cooking Vinyl]]\n* [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[D.A.R.K.|Jetlag]]\n| website = {{URL|cranberries.com}}\n| past_members = \n* Mike Hogan\n* [[Noel Hogan]]\n* Fergal Lawler\n* Niall Quinn\n* [[Dolores O'Riordan]]<!-- Please do not add the notice about her death, as it doesn't belong in the infobox. -->\n}}\n'''The Cranberries''' were an Irish [[Rock music|rock]] band<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/best-cranberries-songs-20-essential-tracks/|title=Limerick alt.rock icons The Cranberries |website=udiscovermusic.com|date=9 October 2019|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> formed in [[Limerick]], Ireland in 1989 by lead singer Niall Quinn, guitarist [[Noel Hogan]], bassist Mike Hogan, and drummer Fergal Lawler. Quinn was replaced as lead singer by [[Dolores O'Riordan]] in 1990.<ref name=\"NYT Hauser\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/15/obituaries/dolores-oriordan-dead.html|title=Celtic-influenced vocals\u2014tuneful, punk-derived, guitar-driven songs|website=New York Times.|date=15 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Ow5Gp|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The band officially classify themselves as an [[alternative rock]] group,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1978669/the-10-best-cranberries-songs/franchises/list/|title=The Cranberries were one of the alt-rock era\u2019s biggest successes.|website=www.stereogum.com|date=16 January 2018 |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/67251/The-Cranberries-No-Need-to-Argue/|title=The Cranberries, a quartet out of Dublin with a rich, clean and mature alternative rock sound.|website=www.sputnikmusic.com|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> but incorporate aspects of [[indie pop]], [[post-punk]], [[folk rock]] and [[pop rock]] into their sound.<ref name=\"UL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ul.ie/ceremonies/cranberries|title='Indie' guitar sound and distinctive Celtic-tinged lilting vocal style.|website=www.ul.ie/ceremonies|date=18 January 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/sJ3Vd|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.post-punk.com/dolores-oriordan-cranberries-passed-away/|title=post-punk.com The Cranberries' lead singer Dolores O'Riordan has died.|website=www.post-punk.com|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/the-cranberries-a-sweet-and-lingering-fruit-of-the-90s-11209817|title=Ireland's biggest export since U2 started off with songs of innocence and became worthy successors of the post-punk movement.|website=news.sky.com/|date=6 September 2018|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@nilegirl/what-the-cranberries-taught-me-about-music-activism-and-love-songs-364bd0e8122|title=The indie-pop/pop-rock/Irish folk group that dominated the earlier part of the nineties.|website=medium.com|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Hauser\"/>\n\nThe Cranberries rose to international fame in the 1990s with their debut album ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'', which became a commercial success, and achieved five top 20 albums on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart : ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'', ''[[No Need to Argue]]'', ''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'', ''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]'' and ''[[Stars: The Best of 1992-2002]]''<ref name=\"US\">{{cite web\n |url=https://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/searchResult.jsp?configType=BBCOM_SIMPLEDEFAULT&pubList=Billboard&an=bbcom&action=Submit&kw=&exposeNavigation=true&keyword=The+Cranberries&submit.x=27&submit.y=14&submit=Submit&searchType=ARTICLE_SEARCH \n |title=American Chart \n |website=Billboard.com \n |accessdate=24 June 2008 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080801201840/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/searchResult.jsp?configType=BBCOM_SIMPLEDEFAULT&pubList=Billboard&an=bbcom&action=Submit&kw=&exposeNavigation=true&keyword=The%2BCranberries&submit.x=27&submit.y=14&submit=Submit&searchType=ARTICLE_SEARCH \n |archivedate=1 August 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> as well as having eight top 20 singles on the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart : \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\", \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\", \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\", \"[[Ode to My Family]]\", \"[[Ridiculous Thoughts]]\", \"[[Salvation (The Cranberries song)|Salvation]]\", \"[[Free to Decide]]\", and \"[[Promises (The Cranberries song)|Promises]]\".<ref name=US />\n<br />Their fifth studio album ''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'' was released in October 2001.\n\nIn early 2009, after a six-year hiatus, the Cranberries reunited and began a North American tour followed by shows in Latin America and Europe.<ref name=\"SPIN.com\">{{cite web| url=https://www.spin.com/2009/11/cranberries-reunite-after-six-years/| title=The Cranberries Reunite After Six Years| website=Spin.com| accessdate=12 November 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Dolores\">{{cite web| url=http://www.doloresoriordan.ie/news-all.asp| title=CRANBERRIES HIT SOUTH AMERICA!/FIRST OFFICIALLY ANNOUNCED TOUR DATE FOR EUROPE!| publisher=Dolores O'Riordan| accessdate=24 December 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831111453/http://www.doloresoriordan.ie/news-all.asp| archivedate=31 August 2009}}</ref> The band recorded their sixth album ''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' in May 2011, and released it in February 2012. ''[[Something Else (The Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'', an album covering many of the band's most popular songs along with new orchestral accompaniments provided by the Irish Chamber Orchestra, was released in April 2017.<ref name=\"pitchfork3-14-2017\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/72242-listen-to-the-cranberries-new-acoustic-version-of-linger/|title=The Cranberries Announce New Acoustic Album Something Else, Share \"Linger\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> The album also included three new songs: \"The Glory\", \"Rupture\" and \"Why?.<ref name=\"SPILL\">{{cite web|url=http://spillmagazine.com/spill-album-review-cranberries-something-else/|title=Three new songs appear on this album: 'The Glory,' 'Rupture,' and 'Why.'|website=spillmagazine.com|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/cranberries-final-sessions-dolores-oriordan/|title=Something Else, which contained acoustic and orchestral takes of 10 of their songs, along with three new tracks, \"The Glory,\" \"Rupture\" and \"Why.\"|website=www.ultimateclassicrock.com|date=7 March 2018|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2018, lead singer [[Dolores O'Riordan]] was found dead of drowning in a London hotel room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/dolores-oriordan-cranberries-lead-vocalist-dies-46|title=Dolores O'Riordan: The Cranberries' Lead Vocalist Dies at 46 |website=www.grammy.com|date=16 January 2018|accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref> She had recently arrived in [[London]] for a studio mixing session on her [[D.A.R.K.]] album and to discuss the band's latest album with record label [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/20/dolores-oriordan-working-new-cranberries-album-died-says-publicist/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/dolores-oriordan-was-working-on-a-new-cranberries-album-before-her-untimely-death-36509243.html|title=The Cranberries frontwoman Dolores O\u2019Riordan was in London to discuss plans for the band\u2019s latest album when she died.|website=www.independent.ie|date=19 January 2018|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> The Cranberries confirmed in September<!-- This confirmation was announced in September, so do not change to November, thank you --> 2018 that they would not continue as a band, releasing their final album ''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' in April 2019 and disbanding afterward.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/cranberries-final-album-in-the-end|title=The Cranberries final album 'In The End' is a celebration of Dolores O'Riordan's talent|website=www.irishcentral.com|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref> Noel Hogan stated: \"the Cranberries was the four of us. We don\u2019t want to do this without Dolores. So we\u2019re going to leave it after this.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/cranberries-talk-everybody-else-is-doing-it-reissue-final-album-with-dolores-o-riordan-731376/|title=The Cranberries on Their Surprise Hit Debut and Final Album With Dolores O\u2019Riordan|first1=Richard|last1=Bienstock|first2=Richard|last2=Bienstock|date=9 October 2018|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Cranberries have sold over 40 million albums worldwide as of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cranberries.com/biography|title=Biography|website=www.cranberries.com|date=12 October 2019|accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/cranberries-new-album-4-16-19/|title=The band have sold more than 40 million albums worldwide.|website=www.bestclassicbands.com|date=16 April 2019|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/hozier-becomes-fourth-irish-artist-reach-no-1-us-22768706|title=Overall, they have sold almost 50 million albums.|website=www.hotpress.com|date=12 March 2019|accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> The band ranks as one of the best-selling alternative acts of the '90s which garnered them an [[MTV Europe Music Award]], a [[World Music Award]], an International Group nomination at [[Brit Awards]], a [[Juno Award|Juno]] nomination and a Juno Award win. The band was nominated for the [[Ivor Novello Awards]] and received an Ivor Novello Award for International Achievement. In 1998 they performed at the [[Nobel Peace Prize Concert]]. In 2016, they received a [[BMI Award]] with a Special Citation of Achievement. ''[[In the End (album)|In The End]]'' earned them a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nomination for Best Rock Album.\n\n==History==\n===Formation and early years (1989\u20131992)===\nBrothers [[Noel Hogan]] and Mike Hogan, descendants of the nineteenth-century Irish poet [[Michael Hogan (poet)|Michael Hogan]], met Fergal Lawler in the mid-1980s.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}}<ref name=\"MD95\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.moderndrummer.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/md191cs.pdf|title=Fergal Lawler|website=Modern Drummer.|year= 1995|publisher=David Frangioni|location=USA|issn=0194-4533|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408192338/https://www.moderndrummer.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/md191cs.pdf|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The young kids who grew up together in [[Limerick]], [[Ireland]], also shared their love of '80s English/[[indie music]] and were \"galvanised by punk\u2019s [[DIY ethic]]\".<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/noel-hogan-cranberries-everybody-else-interview/|title=\"It Was The Perfect Time And Place\"|last=Peacock|first=Tim|website=uDiscoverMusic.|date=19 October 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/rTfBg|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CR2019\">{{cite web|url=https://crypticrock.com/interview-noel-hogan-of-the-cranberries/|title=Interview - Noel Hogan|website=Cryptic Rock.|date=27 December 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/HYnDE|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> Lawler received his first [[drum kit]] as a Christmas present when he was about seventeen; two months later, Mike Hogan received his first [[Bass guitar|bass]] and his brother his first [[Electric guitar|guitar]].<ref name=\"MD95\"/> Niall Quinn who lived in the region already played with his own group called Hitchers and occasionally came often to share his experiences with the trio.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/> Thereafter, they were leaning towards the idea of a four piece ensemble and Quinn stayed with them.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/>\n\nIn mid-1989, brothers Mike, 16, and Noel Hogan, 18, formed The Cranberry Saw Us with drummer Fergal Lawler, 18, and singer Niall Quinn.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=21}}{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=37}} In early 1990, Quinn left them to return to his previous group, although they remained on good terms.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=22}}<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/> Despite this unexpected broke up, the three musicians became an instrumental group during several months, continuing to improve ideas and song structures of instrumental pieces.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/> Lawler and the two Hogan brothers then placed an advertisement for a female singer.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/><ref name=Programme>The Cranberries Loud & Clear World Tour Programme, \"A Timeline of the Cranberries 1989\u2013'99\", pp. 8\u201310.</ref> Subsequently, Quinn suggested to introduce the trio to a friend of his girlfriend's sister, mentioning that she was a singer-songwriter looking for a group who would compose originals.<ref name=\"CR2019\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/>\n\nOn a Sunday afternoon in mid-1990, 18-year-old [[Dolores O'Riordan]] cycled to the audition at Xeric Studios dressed in a tracksuit and with a broken [[Casio keyboard]] under her arm.<ref name=\"HP CLARCK\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/culture/ode-to-dolores-the-full-hot-press-cover-story-on-dolores-oriordan-21734931|title=Ode To Dolores|last=Clark|first=Stuart|website=HotPress.|date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/yfVZX|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\" RS BROWNE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-cranberries-final-album-interview-790271/|title=The Making of the Cranberries' Haunted Farewell|last=Browne|first=David|website=Rolling Stone.|date=7 February 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Bm4us|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> O'Riordan said of the first encounter \"''I really liked what I heard; I thought they were very nice and tight. It was a lovely potential band but they needed a singer - and direction''\".<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/><ref name=\"HP CLARCK\"/> [[Noel Hogan]] gave her a rough cassette demo incorporating chord sequences of indie-[[Jangle|jangly]] guitar sounds, then O'Riordan took home Hogan's tape and began writing lyrics and overlaying melodies which would underpin the group's future material.<ref name=\"RS BROWNE\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> Within a week she returned to the musicians with whom she sang along a rough version of \"Linger\" .<ref name=\"RS BROWNE\"/> Mike Hogan later described it as \"''we were immediately blown away, her voice was something special''\".<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/> Noel Hogan elaborated, \"''she was so small and quiet... then she opened her mouth and this amazing voice, this huge voice came out for the size of her''\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/23/713529217/the-cranberries-final-album-celebrates-the-new-beginning-dolores-o-riordan-wante?t=1575744084687&t=1586214906649|title=Music Interviews|last=Martin|first=Rachel|website=NPR.|date=23 April 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/AkyVD|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> and then acknowledged: \"''how come she\u2019s not already in a band?'' [ ... ] ''that day changed our lives''\".<ref name=\"CR2019\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> A musical relationship rapidly developed between O\u2019Riordan and Noel Hogan who had enough songs to design a demo.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/dolores-oriordan-and-the-cranberries-strange-fruit-72247/|title=The improbable rise of Ireland\u2019s biggest musical export since U2|last=Foege|first=Alec|website=Rolling Stone.|date=23 March 1995|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/TODBm|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The fledgling band recorded a four-track demo EP called ''[[Water Circle]]'', released in cassette format by local record label Xeric Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/the-cranberries-were-the-ultimate-teen-soundtrack-band/|title=The Cranberries|last=Berman|first=Judy|website=Pitchfork.|date=17 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/RHx6S|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/ce9edf12-b5c7-4acd-b008-c5760742342f|title=Water Circle release by The Cranberry Saw Us|website=MusicBrainz.|date=22 September 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/f7YeO|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1990, the group performed their first gig with O'Riordan at an hotel basement called Ruby's Club, Cruises Hotel, Limerick, performing six original songs to an audience of 60 people including three others local groups.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=25}}<ref name=\"HP CLARCK\"/> The Cranberry Saw Us moved to Xeric Recording studio and recorded ''[[Nothing Left at All]]'',{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=24}} a first commercial three-track EP released on tape in 300 copies by Xeric Records, which sold out in local record shops in Limerick within a few days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/870e3053-2561-4961-b487-be542a0817c1|title=Nothing Left at All release by The Cranberry Saw Us|website=MusicBrainz.|date=22 September 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/2HQTq|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whytes.ie/art/the-cranberries-nothing-left-at-all-1990-cassette-tape/144410/?SearchString=&LotNumSearch=&GuidePrice=&OrderBy=LH&ArtistID=&ArrangeBy=list&NumPerPage=15&offset=149|title=Nothing Left At All 1990 cassette tape|website=Whyte's.|date=30 May 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/CUhdl|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The owner of Xeric Studios, Pearse Gilmore, became their manager and provided the group with studio time to complete a demo tape which he produced.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> It featured early versions of \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\" and \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\", which were sent directly to record companies in London by Noel Hogan, determined to leave the [[Underground culture|underground circuit]] of small Irish clubs and pubs.<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/>{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=26}} [[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]] label founder [[Geoff Travis]] immediately gave his approval, although The Cranberries did not sign on his label the demo continued to earn the attention of both the UK [[History of British newspapers|press]] and record industry and sparked a bidding war between major British [[record label]]s.<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/>{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=26}}\n\nOn 18 April 1991, the group played a decisive show in their hometown at [[Shopping centres in Limerick|Jetland Center]] as part of the [[University of Limerick]]\u2019s [[RAG Week]] to 1,400 students.<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/> In attendance was record producer [[Denny Cordell]] who was then [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] for [[Island Records]], and thirty-two other A&R men who flew from [[London]].<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\"/><ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> Shortly thereafter, the band changed their name to \"The Cranberries\".<ref name=\" FANNING91\">{{cite web|url=https://fanningsessions.wordpress.com/2011/02/23/cork-rocks-1991/|title=Cork Rock (1991)|last=Fanning|first=Dave|website=The Fanning Sessions.|date=23 February 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/MNEB|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> ''Nothing Left at All'' began to circulate in [[UK]] with the support of John Best PR agency.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} Then, they performed their first UK tour opening for the British band [[Moose (band)|Moose]] throughout a series of three weeks.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} The Cranberries received more letters expressing interest from [[Virgin Records|Virgin]], [[EMI Records|EMI]], [[Imago Records|Imago]], [[CBS Records International|CBS]], and [[Warner Records|Warner]], which led Hogan brothers to quit their jobs.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> Eventually the group signed to a six albums deal with [[Island Records]] who won the battle.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=25-26}}{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} In mid-1991, The Cranberries headed back into the studio with Gilmore as their producer to record \"''hastily''\" their first EP ''[[Uncertain (EP)|Uncertain]]'' and created a music video for the title track, which was not released.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> Gilmore, in an incoherent gesture, made various alterations to the album's rough cuts.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=27}} 5,000 total copies of ''Uncertain'' were printed and released in October 1991 by [[Island Records]] under the Xeric name.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/3abd4cd5-08af-49bf-bb17-ecd2918847fc|title=Uncertain release by The Cranberries|website=MusicBrainz.|date=12 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/j1i8t|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The EP received poor reviews in the press and led to tension between the group and Gilmore.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=27}} By this time, Gilmore began restricting information to The Cranberries and made separate arrangements with Island\u2019s U.S branch.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> In October 1991 The Cranberries performed at [[Camden Underworld|Underworld]] in London during a UK and Ireland tour.<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> Adding to this period of doubt, touring conditions and money were lacking with maximum earnings of $25 a day.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=25-26}} On 9 December 1991, The Cranberries was supposed to support [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] in [[Belfast]]'s Conor Hall, but Nirvana canceled their tour at the last moment as well as the [[List of Nirvana concerts|five remaining shows]] due to ill health of [[Kurt Cobain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livenirvana.com/concerts/cancelled.php|title=Live Nirvana Concert Chronology - Cancelled Shows|website=LiveNIRVANA.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Sq8vm|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-46509946|title=King's Hall concerts from The Beatles to Nirvana|last=Kearney|first=Joe|website=BBC.|date=12 January 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/0Cbkb|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter a difficult recording session, intended for their [[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?|first album]] on Island Records in January 1992, the band scrapped their work and fired Gilmore.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=27}}<ref name=Programme /> [[Noel Hogan]] stated \"''we didn\u2019t have a problem with each other, we had a problem with this guy''\".<ref name=\"RS FOEGE\"/> During that time period The Cranberries toured in [[Ireland]] and the [[UK]] as opening act for TOP, getting more attention of the British press.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=28}} Subsequently, they hired [[Geoff Travis]] as their new manager,<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK2\"/> The Cranberries headed back into the studio in [[Dublin]] in March 1992 to restart working on their first LP with [[Stephen Street]], who had previously worked with [[The Smiths]].{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}}<ref name=Programme /> The Cranberries began a UK and Ireland headlining tour during the last four months of 1992 to promote the subsequent release of ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]''.{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} In October 1992, \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" was released in the UK, becoming ''[[Melody Maker]]'''s Single of the week.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}} In November 1992, they performed at the emblematic [[Royal Albert Hall]] supporting [[Mercury Rev|Miercury Rev]] and [[The House of Love]].{{sfn|Rees|Crampton|1996|p=248}} Between 1991 and 1993, the band also recorded several [[The Cranberries radio and television sessions|studio and live sessions]] intended for Irish and British radio and television shows, including [[2fm]]'s ''[[The Dave Fanning Show]]'' in Dublin and [[BBC Radio 1]]'s ''[[John Peel]] Show''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pastdaily.com/2018/01/15/dolores-oriordan-1991-past-daily-memorial-edition/|title=Dolores O\u2019Riordan \u2013 The Cranberries In Session \u2013 1991|last=Skene|first=Gordon|website=Past Daily.|date=15 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/bXvYW|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\" FANNING91\"/>\n\n===Mainstream success (1993\u20131995)===\n[[File:The Cranberries at Roxy Bar 1995.jpg|alt=O'Riordan onstage with a large acoustic guitar|thumb|left|upright|O'Riordan singing onstage at the height of their fame, 1995]]\nTheir first full-length album ''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'' was released in March 1993.<ref name=Programme /> Neither the album nor the single gained much attention, nor did a second single, \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\".{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}} When the band embarked on a tour supporting [[Suede (band)|Suede]], they caught the attention of [[MTV]], which put their videos into heavy rotation.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}} The defining moment occurred when mid-way through the tour running order was reversed and The Cranberries replaced Suede as the tour headliners.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/remembering-dolores-o-riordan-can-you-lend-me-20-quid-and-buy-me-a-drink-1.3357191|title=Remembering Dolores O'Riordan|last=Boyd|first=Brian|website=The Irish Times.|date=16 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/6oDIv|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> During the U.S. tour, Linger received heavy rotation on college radio stations across the country.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}} Although \"Linger\" was first released in the UK in February 1993, peaking at 74, it was later re-issued in February 1994 peaking at 14. \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\", the band's first big hit, peaked at number three in Ireland and stayed on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard]] Hot 100 list for 24 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/01/16/zombie-linger-dreams-classic-cranberries-songs-following-dolores-oriordans-tragic-death-7232492/|title=Zombie, Linger, Dreams and more classic The Cranberries songs|website=metro.co.uk|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> This was followed by \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" released again in May 1994 peaking at No.&nbsp;27 on the UK charts and top 15 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard]] Hot 100 list, which helped their debut album to top both the [[UK Album Chart]] and [[Irish Albums Chart|Ireland Album Chart]] in June.<ref name=\"ILL Lynch\"/> In January 1994, Dolores injured her knee when skiing in the Swiss Alps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/9064833/Dolores-ORiordan-I-was-famous-but-I-just-felt-so-isolated.html|title=Skiing accident in Val d'Is\u00e8re|website=www.telegraph.co.uk|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> By 1994, The Cranberries world tour averaged 13,500 attendees at each performance.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=38}}\n\nThe group reunited with Street for ''[[No Need to Argue]]'', which was released in late 1994. It would go on to peak at No.&nbsp;6 on the US charts and eventually outsold its predecessor. Within a year it went triple platinum, spawning the number one hit \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" and the No.&nbsp;11 \"[[Ode to My Family]]\" on the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref name=\"US\" /> By March 1994, The Cranberries won the Top International Act of [[Music Week]] (UK).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/crancyclopedia/biography/|title=Top International Act|website=cranberriesworld.com|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> On 13 August 1994, during their US tour, The Cranberries performed at [[Woodstock '94|Woodstock II]] festival, [[Saugerties, New York|Saugerties]], New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1994-08-13-mn-26772-story.html|title=New Generation of Fans Flocks to Woodstock '94 |last1=J.Goldman|first1=John|last2=Braun|first2=Stephen|website=LA Times.|date=13 August 1994|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/AjEBk|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1995, the band continued to tour, and released two more singles \"[[I Can't Be with You]]\" and \"[[Ridiculous Thoughts]]\". The album went 5\u00d7 platinum in Canada, platinum in Switzerland, and 7\u00d7 platinum in the United States.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web\n |url         = https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=The_Cranberries&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25\n |title       = RIAA Certifications\n |publisher   = [[Recording Industry Association of America]]\n |accessdate  = 24 June 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6ANx0WHyD?url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=The_Cranberries&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&\n |archivedate = 2 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CRIA\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php \n |title=CRIA Certifications \n |publisher=[[Music Canada|CRIA]] \n |accessdate=24 June 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601023939/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php\n |archivedate=1 June 2009\n}}</ref><ref name=\"SWI C\">{{cite web\n| url=http://hitparade.ch/search_certifications.asp?search=The+Cranberries\n| title=SWI Certifications\n| publisher=Switzerland\n| accessdate=24 June 2008 }}</ref>\n[[File:The Cranberries, Washington, D.C., USA, 15 May 1995.jpg|thumb|right|Crowd scene before riot broke out during The Cranberries concert in Washington, D.C. 1995]]\nOn 20 February 1995, The Cranberries received a nomination at the [[Brit Awards]] in the [[Brit Award for International Group|International Group category]], at the 15th edition of the annual pop music awards in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicforstowaways.wordpress.com/2014/01/30/the-brit-awards-1995/|title=The BRIT Awards 1995|website=Music for stowaways.|date=30 January 2014|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/f1624|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ireland-at-the-brit-awards-look-back-at-every-irish-winner-and-nominee__25596/|title=Ireland at the BRIT Awards: look back at every Irish winner and nominee|date=19 January 2019|website=www.officialcharts.com|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> In mid-1995, The Cranberries had broken the American market, at that time the band was Ireland\u2019s biggest musical export since [[U2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-cranberries-have-broken-the-all-important-american-market-americans-clasped-dolores-to-their-1593543.html|title=The Cranberries have broken the all-important American market. |website=www.independent.co.uk/ceremonies|date=28 July 1995|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> On 15 May 1995, The Cranberries had planned an impromptu free acoustic set for 3,000 people at [[National Sylvan Theater]], [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]].<ref name=\"WTOP\">{{cite web|url=https://wtop.com/music/2018/01/time-cranberries-played-free-show-d-c-riot-broke/|title=The Cranberries played a free show in DC \u2014 and a riot broke out|last=Augenstein|first=Neal|website=Washington's Top News.|date=16 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/8tyIo|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\">{{cite news |first=Cesar|last=G. Soriano |authorlink=The Washington Times |title=Concert crowd hits police with rocks|url=https://i.redd.it/4kxz4xx880k21.jpg |format=broadsheet|newspaper=The Washington Times|publisher=Larry Beasley|location=United States|issn=0732-8494|page=5|date=16 May 1995 |language=english|archiveurl=https://archive.today/GRCCb|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"WTOP MP3\">{{Cite episode |title=WTOP's Neal Augenstein recalls The Cranberries in D.C|url=https://wtop.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/1CRANBERRIESnau.mp3 |access-date=11 April 2020|series=WTOP News|last=Augenstein|first=Neal|station=107.7 MHz|date=16 January 2018 |minutes=1|transcript=Top News from WTOP|transcript-url=https://podcastone.com/top-news-from-wtop?showAllEpisodes=true|language=English}}</ref> The show was orchestrated  by radio station [[WHFS (historic)|WHFS]], which had paid for the use of five U.S. [[Park police|Park Police]] officers.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> Before the show began, the organizers promptly realized how erroneous their original crowd estimates were when a frenzied crowd of over 10,000 appeared.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> The Cranberries show started 40 minutes late, while [[stage diving]] started before the first guitar note was played.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> Park Police officers established that they couldn't control the crowd and stopped the show after one song and a half.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> The crowd were told The Cranberries would not be returning and the raging crowd sparked riots throwing rocks, food and beer bottles at the Park Police officers in riot helmets, some jumped onstage and O'Riordan's acoustic guitar was stolen.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> More Police officers in riot gear came in, dozens of [[Mounted police|mounted horse patrols]] established a perimeter and cleared the south quarter of the [[Washington Monument]] grounds as a helicopter circled overhead while the fracas continued outside.<ref name=\"WTOP\"/><ref name=\"TWT Soriano\"/> On 23 May 1995, at London\u2019s [[Grosvenor House]], The Cranberries were nominated for Best Contemporary Song at the [[Ivor Novello Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioswissjazz.ch/en/music-database/band/24104893adafd06a6f0a84c66f4f17a9e56357/biography?app=true|title=Awards and Nominations|website=www.radioswissjazz.ch|date=30 January 2012|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>  In 1995 they performed \"[[Ode to My Family|Ode To my family]]\" at the [[World Music Awards]], winning the Award for Best Irish Recording Artists.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=20}} The Cranberries were named Best Irish Recording Artists at the 10th annual Irish Music awards, held at Dublin's Burlington Hotel.{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=20}}{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}} On 23 November 1995 The Cranberries won the \"Best Song\" award for \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" at the [[1995 MTV Europe Music Awards]], beating out [[Michael Jackson]]'s \u201c[[You Are Not Alone]]\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a1398/in-depth-mtv-europe-music-awards/|title=The 1995 MTV Europe Music Awards - Le Zenith, Paris |website=www.digitalspy.com|date=11 October 2000|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}} During the ''[[No Need To Argue]]'' European tour '95, The Cranberries performed to more than 500,000 people,<ref name=\"UL\"/> with peak attendance reaching 20,000 people per night in [[United States]].<ref name=\"CSM Parney\"/>\n\n===Middle era (1996\u20132000)===\nOn 10 March 1996, The Cranberries received the Best-Selling Album Award for ''[[No Need to Argue]]'' at the 26th Annual [[Juno Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/nomination/1996-best-selling-album-foreign-or-domestic-the-cranberries/|title=Best Selling Album|website=www.junoawards.ca|date=10 March 1996|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilovelimerick.ie/the-cranberries-single-dreams/|title= Juno Award for International Album of the Year, No Need To Argue|website=www.ilovelimerick.ie|date=14 October 2016|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> The band's third album ''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'' peaked at No.&nbsp;2 in the UK and No.&nbsp;4 on the ''[[Billboard 200]]''.<ref name=\"US\" /><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web\n |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/\n |title=British Album Chart \n |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]\n |accessdate=24 June 2008 \n |df= \n}}</ref> ''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'' sells to 4 million copies in six weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/crancyclopedia/biography/|title=To The Faithful Departed sells a striking 4 million copies within six weeks|website=www.cranberriesworld.com|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> Despite favourable reviews, the album did not match the sales of ''No Need to Argue''. The album went double platinum in the US and Gold in the UK.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web\n| url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/index.asp\n| title=BPI Certifications\n| publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]\n| accessdate=24 June 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080424073628/http://www.bpi.co.uk/index.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 24 April 2008}}</ref> The first single from the album was \"[[Salvation (The Cranberries song)|Salvation]]\" which topped the Modern Rock Tracks chart.<ref name=\"US\" /> The second single from the album was \"[[Free to Decide]]\"; the single's peak in the UK was 33<ref name=\"UK\" /> and placing on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].In September 1996, The Cranberries' video for \"Salvation\" was nominated for a MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1996/mtvvmas.htm|title=1996 MTV Video Music Awards|website=Rock on the Net.|date=4 September 1996|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/W0rO|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/mtv-vmas-1996-489.html|title=MTV VMAs 1996|website=Awards and Shows.|date=15 September 1996|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/1HOuC|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In November 1996 \"[[When You're Gone (Cranberries song)|When You're Gone]]\" was released as a single in the United States, peaking at 22 on the Hot 100.<ref name=\"US\" /> In late 1996, the group cancelled their Australian and European tour, O'Riordan re-injured her knee during a concert in [[Cairns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/1996/6/9/19247343/lead-singer-s-knee-injury-forces-cancellation-of-tour|title=Lead Singer's Knee Injury Forces Cancellation of Tour|website=www.deseret.com|date=9 June 1996|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:The Cranberries, Palalido, Italy, April 20, 1999.jpg|thumb|left|The Cranberries performing in Milan, 1999]]\nOn 9 March 1997, [[Bruce Fairbairn]] and The Cranberries were nominees at the [[Juno Award]]s for their work on \"[[Free to Decide]]\" and \"[[When You're Gone (Cranberries song)|When You're Gone]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/nomination/1997-producer-of-the-year-bruce-fairbairn-the-cranberries-co-producers/|title=Producer of the Year 1997|website=www.junoawards.ca|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> The band received an [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for International Achievement, on 19 May 1997, at London\u2019s [[Grosvenor House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicforstowaways.wordpress.com/2018/11/08/ivor-novello-awards-the-1990s/|title=Ivor Novello Awards 1997|website=www.musicforstowaways.wordpress.com|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hessomedia.com/final-album-end-cranberries-charts-10/|title=they have won the Ivor Novello Award for International Achievement.|website=www.hessomedia.com|date=3 May 2019|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 November 1998 [[Dolores O'Riordan]] and Fergal Lawler made an appearance at the [[1998 MTV Europe Music Awards]] in [[Milan]] and presented the award for best song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/crancyclopedia/biography/|title=The band is invited to present the award for Best Song at the MTV European Music Awards|website=cranberriesworld.com|date=12 November 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-mtv-cranberries-106074501.html|title=The Cranberries at the MTV Awards ceremony|website=www.alamy.com|date=12 November 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref> The band played \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\", \"Promises\" and \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\" at [[Nobel Peace Prize Concert|The Nobel Peace Prize Concert]] 1998, on 11 December at [[Oslo Spektrum]], Oslo, [[Norway]]. \"Promises\" is performed live for the first time, four months before the release of the album ''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1427569/alanis-morissette-cranberries-tapped-for-nobel-concert/|title=Cranberries Tapped For Nobel Concert |website=www.mtv.com|date=10 December 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/live/promo-performances/nobel-peace-prize-concert/|title=Nobel Peace Prize Concert  |website=cranberriesworld.com|date=10 December 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/1998/summary/|title=The Nobel Peace Prize 1998|website=www.nobelprize.org|date=16 October 1998|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, The Cranberries released ''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]''. The first single \"Promises\" was released in February. \"Promises\" would be the only single from the album to chart in the US and last single before their hiatus.<ref name=\"US\" /> The album peaked at 7 in the UK and 13 in the US<ref name=\"US\" /><ref name=\"UK\" /> and was certified gold in the US.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> The second single from the album was \"[[Animal Instinct (Cranberries song)|Animal Instinct]]\", which didn't chart in the UK, although it did chart in France, Austria and many others.<ref name=\"IRE\">{{cite web\n| url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Cranberries&titel=Animal+Instinct&cat=s\n| title=Chart\n| website=Lescharts.com\n| accessdate=24 June 2008 }}</ref> The third and fourth singles were \"Just My Imagination\" and \"You & Me\", respectively. The band had a guest appearance on popular television series ''[[Charmed]]'', performing \"[[Just My Imagination (Cranberries song)|Just My Imagination]]\" on the fifth episode of the second season, \"[[Charmed (season 2)#Episode list|She's a Man, Baby, a Man!]]\". The group started a world tour in April 1999 and it finished in July 2000. The group partnered with Ticketmaster.com to be the first artists to sell tickets for a national tour exclusively online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1999/biz/news/tix-selling-quick-for-ticketmaster-online-1117493279/|title=Tix selling quick for Ticketmaster Online|website=variety.com|date=15 April 1999 |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref> It was the biggest and most successful tour of the Cranberries' career.<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\">{{cite magazine |last=Sexton|first=Paul|date=27 October 2001|title=Cranberries 'Wake' To New Beginning |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=kBEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=the+cranberries&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIjYyQpMrnAhURxIUKHdoXA7oQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|magazine=Billboard |location=USA|volume=113|issue=43|page=14|publisher=Nielsen Business Media Inc.|issn=0006-2510|url-status=live|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> The tour brought them back to Ireland for their first date since May 2000. They performed at [[Millstreet]] in [[County Cork]]. As the tour rolled on, the band released ''Bury The Hatchet&nbsp;\u2013 The Complete Sessions'', a double CD featuring B-sides as well as live tracks taken from a show in Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishmusicdaily.com/cranberries-no-need-to-argue|title=Cranberries' Most Successful Tour|website=www.irishmusicdaily.com|date=1 November 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Later years (2001\u20132003)===\nIn October 2001, the album ''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'' was released.<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\"/> The band's old producer [[Stephen Street]] had returned and produced their new music video.<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\"/> The album peaked at 46 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],<ref name=\"US\" /> No. 2 on Spanish, Italian and French album charts. It went to No. 8 in Canada's Billboard Chart and reached No. 61 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pure-music.co.uk/wake-up-and-smell-the-coffee-album-cover/|title=\"Wake Up And Smell The Coffee\" is the fifth studio album released by Irish alternative rock band The Cranberries.|website=www.pure-music.co.uk|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"UK\" /> The first single released from the album was \"[[Analyse (Cranberries song)|Analyse]]\", which charted in the US Adult Top 40 at a peak of 26.<ref name=\"US\" /><ref name=\"UK\" /> In January 2002, they released the second single \"[[Time Is Ticking Out]]\", and some months later another one, \"This Is the Day\".\nThe Cranberries was managed by ''Timeless Management'' in [[London]].<ref name=\"BTH Sexton\"/>\n\nThe following year a greatest hits album was released entitled ''[[Stars&nbsp;\u2013 The Best of 1992\u20132002]]'' which was released alongside an [[Stars - The Best of 1992 - 2002 (DVD)|eponymous DVD]] of [[music video]]s. The album peaked in the UK at 20.<ref name=\"UK\" /> The song \"[[Stars (The Cranberries song)|Stars]]\" was released as a single from that album. They started a European tour in mid-October 2002 and ended in December.\n\nIn January 2003, following advice from their legal advisors, The Cranberries parted ways with record [[MCA Records|label MCA]], due to the band's dissatisfaction with the ''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'''s promotion.<ref name=\"BB MCA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/72598/cranberries-terminate-mca-contract|title=Cranberries Terminate MCA Contract|website=Billboard.|date=22 January 2003|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/PwZxH|archivedate=13 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HP MCA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/cranberries-split-from-mca-2634515|title=Cranberries split from MCA|website=Hot Press.|date=21 January 2003|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/eRASH|archivedate=13 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> [[Noel Hogan]] observed \"''with little effort from our label, we have been pleased to see top-10 sales in many countries''\".<ref name=\"BB MCA\"/> Despite comments from MCA regarding that the album didn't reach the [[Billboard 200]]'s top 30, the 2002 concerts drew an average audience of 10,000 people, with many of the dates selling-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/34thanks-to-our-incredibly-supportive-fans-we-say-fuck-em34-2613266|title=We say 'fuck 'em' - Thanks to our incredibly supportive fans|website=Hot Press.|date=19 September 2002|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/53kr4|archivedate=13 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HP MCA\"/> O'Riordan told ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'': \"''since we were signed in 1991 by Island Records, we have gradually seen our label dissolve from a pioneering independent spirited label into a corporate monolith that completely lost touch with the group's creative vision''\".<ref name=\"BB MCA\"/> The Cranberries signed in 1991 with [[Island Records]] America which was transferred to [[MCA Records|MCA]] in 2000 following a contract renegotiation.<ref name=\"HP MCA\"/><ref name=\"BB MCA\"/>\n\nAt the end of February 2003, the Cranberries started working with [[Stephen Street]] and debuted their work for the first time in [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland, on 29 May 2003 performing the songs \"Astral Projection\" and \"In it Together\".<ref name=\"IT2007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/dolores-stories-1.1295395|title=Dolores stories|website=Irish Times.|date=27 April 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/HlPLA/mQRyg|archivedate=27 April 2007|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolesmag.com/article-1252-The-Cranberries-Tomorrow.html|title=The Cranberries \"Roses\"|website=Idoles Mag.|date=31 January 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/DDMMd|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> In September 2003, the band announced they were taking some time to pursue individual careers, as well as concentrate on family, and scrapped sessions for a sixth studio release.<ref name=\"HP 2003\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotpress.com/The-Cranberries/news/The-Cranberries-are-NOT-going-to-split/2679953.html|title=The Cranberries are NOT going to split|author=The Hot Press Newsdesk|website=Hot Press.|date=17 September 2003|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/vbexN|archivedate=9 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Initially, a two-year sabbatical was confirmed, while O'Riordan assured that the group would just take a hiatus, she said \"''we've been together for 13 years; it's a much needed break. It was getting predictable and lacking in a challenge; time to experiment''\".<ref name=\"HP 2003\"/> Althought a spokesperson for The Cranberries announced a \"temporary shutdown in activities\", the four members remained on good terms and in regular contact with each other.<ref name=\"HP 2003\"/>\n\nBetween 1994 and 2003, The Cranberries undertook several world tours and performed in front of crowds of 10,000 to 20,000 each night.{{sfn|Bianco|Knight|1998|p=40}}<ref name=\"UL\"/><ref name=\"CSM Parney\">{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1995/0811/11111.html|title=The Cranberries Prove Red Hot on Beginning Leg of US Tour|last=Leigh Parney|first=Lisa|website=The Christian Science Monitor.|date=11 August 1995|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/4ABox|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Hiatus and solo careers (2004\u20132008)===\n[[File:Dolores O'Riordan.jpg|alt=O'Riordan singing with a guitarist behind her|thumb|O'Riordan singing solo, 2007]]\n[[Dolores O'Riordan]] started collaborating with other musicians in 2004 before launching her solo career with the album ''[[Are You Listening? (Dolores O'Riordan album)|Are You Listening?]]'' in 2007 and a world tour, following it with ''[[No Baggage]]'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Ferguson|first=Tom|date=8 August 2009|title=Baggage Packed |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=lCUF-Ml_lBYC&pg=PT25&dq=dolores+o%27riordan+no+baggage+are+you+listening+world+tour+2007&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwif677VxePoAhW66uAKHUMIAOAQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q&f=false|magazine=Billboard |location=USA|volume=121|issue=31|page=26|publisher=Nielsen Business Media Inc.|issn=0006-2510|url-status=live|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/cranberries-dolores-oriordan-dies-46/|title=The Cranberries\u2019 Vocalist Dolores O\u2019Riordan|last=Peacock|first=Tim|website=uDiscoverMusic|date=15 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/u7z33|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockhermag.com/index.php/2007/05/16/dolores-oriordan-tour-dates-formally-of-the-cranberries/|title=North America 2007|website=Rockher Mag.|date=15 May 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20T9F|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Dolores O'Riordan performed \"[[Linger (song)|Linger]]\" in the 2006 movie [[Click (2006 film)|''Click'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0389860/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Click (2006) Full Cast & Crew|website=IMDB.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/c8Ncf|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Noel Hogan]] started a new project called [[Mono Band]], writing all instrumentation in his own personal studio and developing a \"new way of working\" with programmer Matt Vaughan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/life-after-cranberries-neil-hogan-launches-monoband-2764643|title=Neil Hogan launches Monoband|website=Hot Press.|date=12 November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/mDMq3|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IR2004\">{{cite web|url=https://irishrockers.com/artistView.php?artist=Mono%20Band|title=About Mono Band|website=IrishRockers.com|date=1 November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/qWUhs/mDMq3|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IT2007\"/> The project, whose first full-length self-titled album saw a limited release in 2005, also featured diverse guest musicians as [[Oxford]] singer-songwriter [[Richard Walters (singer-songwriter)|Richard Walters]].<ref name=\"IR2004\"/> Subsequently, Hogan decided to work mainly with Richard Walters, then Mono Band became [[Arkitekt]] whose two EP  were released in 2007 and 2009.<ref name=\"HP2007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/mono-band-change-name-3876248|title=Mono Band change name|website=Hot Press.|date=27 April 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/O0ni8|archivedate=12 July 2007|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishmusicdb.com/a/arkitekt/band_biography.htm|title=Arkitekt - biography|website=Irish Music DB.|date=1 November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/ulvmW|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://irishrockers.com/artistView.php?id=649|title=Arkitekt|website=IrishRockers.com|date=31August 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/mQRyg|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> He has also been working as a producer with Supermodel Twins, from his native Limerick and Remma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingtunes.com/supermodeltwins|title=Supermodel Twins|website=Breakingtunes.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/q1Q8T|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishmusicdb.com/r/remma/band_singles.htm|title=Remma - band - singles|website=Irish Music DB.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/iuyjw|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, Mike Hogan and his wife Siobh\u00e1n opened a [[caf\u00e9]] called ''The Sage Caf\u00e9'', on Catherine Street in the heart of [[Limerick City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilovelimerick.ie/business-directory-2/the-sage-cafe/|title=Business Name: The Sage Caf\u00e9|last=Maher|first=Conor|website=I Love Limerick.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/wZOYe|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The award-winning caf\u00e9 closed on 25 September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.limerickpost.ie/2017/09/25/limerick-sage-cafe-closes/|title=Limerick Sage Cafe closes|date=25 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/fJx7w|archivedate=12 July 2007|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Mike Hogan also played bass with [[Mono Band]].<ref name=\"IT2007\"/>\n\nFergal Lawler was a member of The Low Network, whose first album was released in 2007.<ref name=\"IT2007\"/><ref name=\"HP2007\"/> He has also worked with Walter Mitty and the Realist as well as Last Days of Death Country as both producer and musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockandrollreport.com/the-rock-and-roll-report-band-of-the-week-is-walter-mitty-the-realists/|title=Walter Mitty & The Realists|last=Boudreau|first=Mark|website=The Rock and Roll Report.|date=20 October 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/OtR1R|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingtunes.com/lastdaysofdeathcountry|title=Last Days Of Death Country|website=Breakingtunes.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/kvEi0|archivedate=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reunion and ''Roses'' (2009\u20132015)===\nThe Cranberries reunited in January 2009 to celebrate O'Riordan becoming an Honorary Patron<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|title=The Cranberries|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/apr/02/the-cranberries-review|date=2 April 2010|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Allison|last=Bray|title=Why it's all smelling of 'Roses' for the Cranberries|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/why-its-all-smelling-of-roses-for-the-cranberries-26824540.html|newspaper=[[Independent.ie]]|date=23 February 2012}}</ref> of [[University Philosophical Society (Trinity College, Dublin)]]. The group indicated at the time that this did not signify an official reunion, but on 25 August 2009, in anticipation of the release of ''[[No Baggage]]'', O'Riordan announced that the Cranberries would be reuniting for a North American and European tour.<ref>[http://www.ianaaron.eu/?p=11250] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720163119/http://www.ianaaron.eu/?p=11250|date=20 July 2011}}</ref> O'Riordan indicated that the band would be playing songs from her solo albums and a lot of the Cranberries' classic hits as well as some new group compositions.\n[[File:The Cranberries Live @ Montreal (8375953017).jpg|alt=The band onstage|thumb|The Cranberries reformed in 2012, from left to right: Fergal Lawler, Dolores O'Riordan, and Mike Hogan (Noel Hogan off camera)]]\nAt this point of their career, The Cranberries were managed by Danny Goldberg, former [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and [[Kurt Cobain]] manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternativenation.net/clone/cranberries-dolores-oriordan-revealed-avoided-kurt-cobains-fate-eerie-interview/|title=Late Cranberries singer Dolores O\u2019Riordan discussed Kurt Cobain|first=Brett|last=Buchanan|website=www.alternativenation.net|date=18 January 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/mMv0I|archivedate=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citizen.org/about/person/danny-goldberg/|title=Danny Goldberg Public Citizen Inc.|website=www.citizen.org|date=15 January 2010|archiveurl=https://archive.today/nwrW3|archivedate=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/roses-mw0002278143/credits|title=The Cranberries, Danny Goldberg Management|website=www.allmusic.com|date=4 February 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624032244/https://www.allmusic.com/album/roses-mw0002278143/credits|archivedate=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref> In 2011, the actual ''[[Water Circle]]'' demo tape emerged, widely assumed to be the first appearance of The Cranberries with the vocal of [[Dolores O'Riordan]]. A private collector from [[United States]] submitted the bid to US$1499.95 via [[eBay]] store; the offer was eclipsed later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lyricshall.com/albums/The+Cranberries/Water+Circle+EP/|title=Water Circle EP The Cranberries|website=Lyricshall.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/wCb8e|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618025659/https://www.ebay.com/itm/350154208726?hash=item5186d135d6 |title=The Cranberries Water Circle 1990 first demo tape RARE |author= eBay user \"retro*dream\" |date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Cranberries recorded ''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' at the [[Metalworks Studios]] in [[Mississauga]], Canada, from 18 April<ref name=\"cranberries.com\">[http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#165] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721084220/http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#165|date=21 July 2011}}</ref> to 15 May<ref>{{cite tweet|user=noelhogan2|author-link=Noel Hogan|number=69889310895243264|date=15 May 2011|title=Okay, that's it. Album No.&nbsp;6 recorded, everyone is great spirits after listening. On to London for strings & Steve to mix it after that|accessdate=15 January 2018}}{{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref> 2011 with Stephen Street,<ref name=\"cranberries.com\"/> who previously collaborated with the band on their first, second and fifth albums. The Cranberries worked on 15&nbsp;tracks during the ''Roses'' session, although not all were included on the album.<ref>[http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#166]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721084220/http://www.cranberries.com/news-all.asp#166|date=21 July 2011}}</ref> ''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' was released on 27 February 2012.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cranberries.com/#roses|title=The Cranberries: ''Roses''|website=Cranberries.com|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> The sixth studio album ''Roses'' peaked at 51 on the [[Billboard 200]] chart and had numerous position in Billboard charts as No. 4 on [[Independent Albums]] chart, No. 6 on [[Canadian Albums Chart|Canadian Albums chart]], No. 9 on Alternative Albums chart, No. 10 on Rock Albums chart and No. 20 on Tastmaker Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cranberriesworld.com/2012/03/08/roses-on-the-billboard-charts/|title=\"Roses\" on the Billboard charts.|website=cranberriesworld.com|date=8 March 2012|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February 2012 The Cranberries returned to the stage of the [[Teatro Ariston|Ariston Theatre]] where they presented their new single \"Tomorrow\" in Sanremo at the 62nd [[Sanremo Music Festival|Song Festival di Sanremo]], Italy. They performed \"Tomorrow\" and \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\", having been invited on more than one occasion to the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.melodicamente.com/sanremo-2012-cranberries-ospiti-finale/|title=Sanremo 2012: Cranberries|website=www.melodicamente.com|date=19 February 2012|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2013, The Cranberries album designer [[Storm Thorgerson]] died. The English graphic designer, mainly influenced by surrealism, designed ''Bury The Hatchet'' and ''Wake Up And Smell The Coffee''. Thorgerson also created artworks for these two album\u2019s singles and \u201c[[Beneath the Skin \u2013 Live in Paris|Beneath The Skin]]\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/arts/music/storm-thorgerson-69-pink-floyd-album-cover-artist-dies.html|title=Storm Thorgerson, Album Designer, Dies at 69|first=Bruce|last=Weber|website=NY Times.|date=20 April 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102221535/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/arts/music/storm-thorgerson-69-pink-floyd-album-cover-artist-dies.html|archivedate=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawsons.co.uk/blog/legendary-album-artwork-designer-storm-thorgerson-passes-away|title=Legendary Album Artwork Designer Storm Thorgerson Has Died|website=Dawsons.|date=20 April 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514162342/https://www.dawsons.co.uk/blog/legendary-album-artwork-designer-storm-thorgerson-passes-away|archivedate=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nO'Riordan started legal proceedings against [[Noel Hogan]] in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Owens|first=Alan|title=Cranberries stars could face off in the High Court|url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/what-s-on/arts-entertainment/music/cranberries-stars-could-face-off-in-the-high-court-1-5621794|work=Limerick Leader|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref> The case was struck out in July 2015 and the cause was not divulged.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/news/local-news/111394/Dolores-O-Riordan-due-in-court.html| title=Dolores O\u2019Riordan due in court over air rage incident | work=Limerick Leader| accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nO'Riordan began recording new material with [[D.A.R.K.]] in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jetlagnyc.blogspot.com/search/label/info| title=About Jetlag NYC|website=Jetlagnyc.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n\n===O'Riordan's death, ''In the End'' and disbandment (2016\u20132019)===\n[[File:Dolores O'Riordan, The Cranberries, Bospop, 2016.jpeg|thumb|left|upright|O'Riordan performing during The Cranberries Summer Tour 2016]]\nIn October 2016, The Cranberries received a [[BMI Award]] in [[London]] for three million radio plays in the [[United States]] of their single \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" taken from their [[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?|debut studio album]].<ref name=\"ILL Lynch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ilovelimerick.ie/the-cranberries-single-dreams/|title=Dreams reaches 3mill radio plays in USA|last=Lynch|first=Richard|website=I Love Limerick.|date=14 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/XnDIw|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"UM2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umusic.ca/press-releases/the-cranberries-release-everybody-else-is-doing-it-so-why-cant-we-25th-anniversary-box-set-out-october-19/|title=Broadcast Music, Inc (BMI) Award|website=Umusic.|date=30 August 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/lmQYt|archivedate=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The award had been presented with a special citation of achievement.<ref name=\"ILL Lynch\"/><ref name=\"UM2018\"/>\n\nA new acoustic Cranberries album titled ''[[Something Else (Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'' was released on 28 April 2017, through [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]].<ref name=\"pitchfork3-14-2017\" /> ''[[Something Else (Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'' featured orchestral arrangements of prior releases, re-recorded in 2016 acoustically with the [[Irish Chamber Orchestra]], and three new songs : \"The Glory\", \"Why\", and \"Rupture\".<ref name=\"SPILL\"/>\n\nWith the release of the new album, the group announced a tour which was to include dates in Europe, parts of the UK, and North America. The shows were scheduled in smaller venues, with live orchestral accompaniment. However, in May 2017, shortly into the European tour, The Cranberries had to cancel the remainder of the European dates due to O'Riordan's health, with the band's website citing \"medical reasons associated with a back problem\".<ref name=BBCobituary>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42702826|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Dolores O'Riordan: Voice of a rebel|date=16 January 2018}}</ref> The North American tour dates were cancelled in July when her recovery had not progressed enough for her to participate.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cranberries \u2013 Maison Symphonique, Montr\u00e9al \u2013 Tickets|url=https://www.greenland.ca/event/view/the-cranberries-maison-symphonique-montreal-2017-09-23-tickets-1619|website=Greenland.ca|accessdate=7 October 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2018, O'Riordan died unexpectedly in London, England.<ref name=RTE15jan2018>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/0115/933523-dolores-oriordan-dies-suddenly-in-london|title=Dolores O'Riordan suddenly dies in London|work=RTE news|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref> The inquest into her death was adjourned until 3 April while the coroner awaited the results of \"various tests\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-42745624|title=Dolores O'Riordan inquest awaits tests|date=2018|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> On 6 September 2018, it was ruled that she had [[drowned]] in her hotel room's [[bathtub]] due to sedation by [[alcohol poisoning]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-45434898|title=Cranberries singer O'Riordan died by drowning|date=2018-09-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-09-06|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March 2018, the band announced they were releasing a special newly remastered 25th anniversary edition of their debut album ''Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We'', with previously unreleased material as well as other bonus material from the time of the album. However, with O'Riordan's death it was delayed until 19 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheCranberries/posts/10155531977667106|title=The Cranberries \u2013 Posts|publisher=[[Facebook]]|date=7 March 2018|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref> The band also decided to complete their new album underway at the time O'Riordan died, for which she had already recorded the vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cranberries.com/site/|title=The Cranberries \u2013 Home|accessdate=8 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311061823/http://www.cranberries.com/site/|archive-date=11 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Noel Hogan confirmed the Cranberries would not be continuing as a band, and their final album will be called ''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' stating: \"We will do this album and then that will be it. No one wants to do this without Dolores...<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-cranberries-open-up-about-the-last-days-of-singer-dolores-o-riordan-she-was-on-a-roll__24108/|title=\"She was on a roll\": The Cranberries on the last days of Dolores O\u2019Riordan|website=Officialcharts.com|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref> So there\u2019s a song called 'In the End', it\u2019s the last song on the album, and it just kind of summed up the whole album and the band. Because it\u2019s definitely the end of it for us. So we\u2019ve called it that.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> On 15 January 2019, one year after O'Riordan's death, the band released the first single from ''In the End'', called \"All Over Now\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnewsnet.com/2019/01/the-cranberries-share-first-single-all-over-now-from-final-album-in-the-end.html|title=The Cranberries share first single \u2013 \"All Over Now\" \u2013 from final album, In The End|website=Music News Net}}</ref> The Cranberries released their 8th and final album ''[[In the End (album)|In The End]]'' on 26 April 2019. The album peaked at No. 8 in [[Germany]], No. 5 in [[France]], No. 4 in [[Italy]], No. 3 in [[Ireland]] and charted in the Top 10 of the [[UK Albums Chart|UK Official Charts]]. ''In The End'' went to No. 7 on the Billboard [[Independent Albums]] chart and No. 10 on the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Top Alternative Albums chart<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cranberries.com/news/48-in-the-end-chart-positions-so-far|title=In The End chart positions so far...|website=www.cranberries.com|date=4 May 2018|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> The band released the single \"Wake Me When It's Over\" on 19 June 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnewsnet.com/2019/03/music-news-often-bands-aspire-to-be-timeless-or-to-have-a-sound-that-transcends-the-whims-of-musical-fashion-the-cranberr.html|title=THE CRANBERRIES RELEASE SINGLE \"WAKE ME WHEN IT'S OVER\", NEW \"IN THE END\" ALBUM OUT 4/26/19|website=Music News Net}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2019, [[Noel Hogan]], Mike Hogan and Fergal Lawler were conferred with [[honorary doctorate]]s by [[University of Limerick]] (UL). The posthumous award was presented to Eileen O'Riordan, mother of the band's lead singer [[Dolores O'Riordan]]. They were all presented with an Honorary Doctorate of Letters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/the-cranberries-honorary-doctorate-university-of-limerick/|title=The Cranberries will receive an honorary doctorate from University of Limerick|date=15 January 2019|website=irishcentral|accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Post-disbandment (mid-2019\u2013present)===\n[[Saint Sister]], a duo from [[Northern Ireland]], performed an acapella rendition of the song \"[[Dreams (The Cranberries song)|Dreams]]\" at [[Lyra McKee]]'s funeral in Belfast,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/live-lyra-mckee-funeral-belfast-14545166|title=Lyra McKee funeral: Updates as loved ones pay moving tribute to murdered journalist|website=Daily Mirror|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> who was murdered by the [[Real Irish Republican Army|New IRA]] in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-479854696|title=Lyra McKee murder: Journalist shot dead during Derry rioting|website=www.bbc.com|date=19 April 2019|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nNoel Hogan joined [[Kodaline]] on stage on 1 September 2019, at the [[Electric Picnic|Electric Picnic Festival]] in [[Stradbally]], [[Ireland]], to play \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" in tribute to [[Dolores O'Riordan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonmusic.co.uk/news/electric-picnic-2019-ends-with-explosive-performances-from-florence-johnny-marr-more|title=Kodaline and Hogan tore through an stirring version of 'Zombie'|website=www.eonmusic.co.uk|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe music video restoration campaign of the entire catalogue of The Cranberries on [[YouTube]] was launched on 3 October 2019, twenty-five years after the release of the album ''[[No Need to Argue]]'', with the debut of an early \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" concert performance filmed in 1994 at [[London Astoria|London's Astoria]], remastered in high definition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/video-cranberries-zombie-youtube/|title= Irish band\u2019s catalogue-spanning video restoration campaign|website=www.udiscovermusic.com|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" is performed seven months before the song was released as a single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/cranberries-zombie-live-video-893659/|title= Watch the Cranberries Tear Through Early Version of 'Zombie' |website=www.rollingstone.com|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-cranberries-official-music-videos-to-be-released-in-remastered-high-definition-video-exclusively-on-youtube-300929371.html|title=official \"Zombie\" video's newly remastered 4K HD version|website=www.prnewswire.com|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, in an interview for ''Rock Art Fashion'', Fergal Lawler commented that the band would release a remastered edition of their album ''[[No Need to Argue]]'' as part of a 25th anniversary box set.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rockartfashion.net/2019/04/28/in-the-end-the-final-album-of-the-cranberries-interview-with-fergal-lawler/#English-Version|title=\"In The End\", the final album|website=Rock Art Fashion.|date=28 April 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/aujr9|archivedate=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 November 2019, The Cranberries' final album ''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' has been nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]] at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/cranberries|title=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|website=www.grammy.com|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2019/1120/1094090-the-cranberries-among-grammy-award-nominees/|title=The Cranberries among Grammy Award nominees|website=www.rte.ie|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2020, the official music video for \"[[Zombie (song)|Zombie]]\" became the first song by an Irish band to reach over one billion views on [[Youtube]], becoming the third video from the 1990s, and the sixth from the [[20th century]], to reach the milestone on the video streaming service.<ref name=\"RTE Crowley\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2020/0418/1132342-the-cranberries-join-youtubes-billion-hall-of-fame/|title=The Cranberries join YouTube's billion Hall of Fame |last=Crowley|first=Caroline|website=RTE.|date=18 April 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/PbfTN|archivedate=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nova.ie/the-cranberries-zombie-video-hits-1-billion-views-177630/|title=The Cranberries \"Zombie\" Video Hits 1 Billion Views|last=Drieberg|first=Clint|website=Nova.ie|date=18 April 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Cu4uK|archivedate=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> The Cranberries now joined a club of artists to reach this landmark including [[Guns N\u2019 Roses]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and [[A-ha]].<ref name=\"RTE Crowley\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.limerickleader.ie/news/home/535935/we-are-sure-dolores-has-a-big-proud-smile-on-her-face-limericks-most-famous-group-smashbillion-landmark.html|title=\"We are sure Dolores has a big, proud smile on her face\"|last=Fitzgerald|first=Aine|website=Limerick Leader.|date=18 April 2020|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/Mtq58|archivedate=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\n[[File:Noel-Hogan.jpg|alt=Hogan looking to the camera|thumb|upright|Co-founder and guitarist Noel Hogan has co-written many of the band's songs.]]\nTheir music has been likened [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] and [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]].<ref>{{cite web |first=J.D. |last=Considine |title=There's no disputing the power and emotion in Cranberries' mournful melodies |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-10-04/features/1994277164_1_oriordan-zombie-aow |work=Baltimoresun |date= 4 October 1994|accessdate= 1 February 2017}}</ref> O'Riordan stated her singing style incorporating yodelling was inspired by her father who used to sing \"The Lonesome Cattle Call\": \"I just kept with my father all the time, just copying him and eventually I learned how to do it. Then over the years there were artists like Sin\u00e9ad O\u2019Connor and Siouxsie from Siouxsie and the Banshees and even Peter Harvey was doing it. It was something that you could work into The Cranberries' format because a lot of that was used in religious Irish music\".<ref name=\"PM BRODSKY\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/the-cranberries.html |title=The Cranberries Talk 25th Anniversary, '90s Nostalgia|first=Rachel |last=Brodsky |work=Pastemagazine. |date=28 April 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/P5Vf6|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> O'Riordan was influenced by [[Gregorian chant]], Irish folk music, classical piano, listening to [[Duran Duran]], [[The Cure]], [[Depeche Mode]], and [[The Smiths]].{{sfn|Reisfeld|1996|p=23}}<ref name=\"PM BRODSKY\"/> Lawler, Mike and Noel Hogan, were inspired by [[The Cure]],<ref name=\"MD95\"/> [[Joy Division]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> [[Echo & the Bunnymen]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> [[The Clash]],<ref name=\"UM2018\"/> and [[The Smiths]].<ref name=\"MD95\"/> Noel Hogan stressed that at their beginnings, \"All these roads led to [[The Smiths]], who became very big in our lives later on.\"<ref name=\"UDM PEACOCK1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/cranberries-25th-everybody-else/|title=25th anniversary edition of \"Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can\u2019t We?\"|last=Peacock|first=Tim|website=uDiscoverMusic.|date=30 August 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/9OM2u|archivedate=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n'''Former'''\n*Niall Quinn \u2013 lead vocals, rhythm guitar (1989\u20131990)\n* Mike Hogan&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] (1989\u20132003, 2009\u20132019)\n* [[Noel Hogan]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead guitar|lead and occasional rhythm guitar]], backing vocals (1989\u20132003, 2009\u20132019)\n* Fergal Lawler&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]] (1989\u20132003, 2009\u20132019)\n* [[Dolores O'Riordan]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Singing|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar|rhythm and occasional lead guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]]s (1990\u20132003, 2009\u20132018; died 2018)\n\n'''Touring musicians'''\n* Russell Burton&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards, rhythm guitar (1996\u20132003, 2012)\n* [[Steve DeMarchi]]&nbsp;\u2013 rhythm guitar, backing vocals (1996\u20132003)\n* [[Denny DeMarchi]]&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards, rhythm guitar, backing vocals (2009\u20132011)\n* Johanna Cranitch&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals (2012\u20132017)\n* Ol\u00e9 Koretsky&nbsp;\u2013  rhythm guitar (2017)\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|The Cranberries discography}}\n'''Studio albums'''\n*''[[Everybody Else Is Doing It, So Why Can't We?]]'' (1993)\n*''[[No Need to Argue]]'' (1994)\n*''[[To the Faithful Departed]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Bury the Hatchet (album)|Bury the Hatchet]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Wake Up and Smell the Coffee]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Roses (The Cranberries album)|Roses]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Something Else (The Cranberries album)|Something Else]]'' (2017)\n*''[[In the End (album)|In the End]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==